{"title_page": "Glyn Ford", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox MEP\n| image=\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Glyn Ford\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]]\n| constituency_MP = [[South West England (European Parliament constituency)|South West England]]\n| parliament = European\n| majority =\n| predecessor = ''[[European Parliamentary Elections Act 1999|Constituency established]]''\n| successor = ''Seat abolished''\n| term_start = 1 May 1999\n| term_end = 14 July 2009\n| office2 = Leader <br> [[European Parliamentary Labour Party]]\n| parliament2 = \n| term_start2 = 1989\n| term_end2 = 1993\n| majority2 =\n| predecessor2 =\n| successor2 =\n| office3 = Member of the European Parliament <br> for [[Greater Manchester East (European Parliament constituency)|Greater Manchester East]]\n| parliament3 = \n| term_start3 = 14 June 1984\n| term_end3 = 10 June 1999\n| majority3 =\n| predecessor3 = ''Constituency established''\n| successor3 = ''Constituency abolished''\n|office4     = Member of [[Tameside (borough)|Tameside Borough Council]]\n|term_start4 = ?\n|term_end4  = ?\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1950|01|28|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Gloucester]], England, United Kingdom\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| spouse =\n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[University of Reading]]<br>[[University College London]]\n| occupation =\n| profession = Academic\n| religion =\n| signature =\n| website = [https://web.archive.org/web/20140504205318/http://glynford.org/ glynford.org]\n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''Glyn Ford''' (born 28 January 1950) is a former [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] [[member of the European Parliament]] (1984\u20132009), initially for [[Greater Manchester East (European Parliament constituency)|Greater Manchester East]] until 1999, then [[South West England (European Parliament constituency)|South West England]] from 1999 to 2009.<ref name=ep-profile>{{cite web |url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/1413/GLYN_FORD_home.html |title=Glyn FORD |publisher=European Parliament |accessdate=4 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nFord was born in [[Gloucester]].<ref name=ep-profile/> He went to [[Marling School]], [[Stroud]]. After a year as an apprentice at the [[British Aircraft Corporation]] he returned to education gaining a degree in Geology from the [[University of Reading]] in 1972, then a master's degree in marine Earth science from [[University College London]] in 1974.<ref name=debretts>{{cite web |url=http://www.debretts.com/people-of-today/profile/17473/%28James%29-Glyn-FORD |title=(James) Glyn FORD |publisher=Debretts |work=People of Today |accessdate=4 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923230908/http://www.debretts.com/people-of-today/profile/17473/%28James%29-Glyn-FORD |archivedate=23 September 2015 }}</ref><ref name=eias-cv>{{cite web |url=http://www.eias.org/luncheons/ford150404/glynfordcv.pdf |title=Mr. Glyn Ford MEP: Brief CV |publisher=European Institute for Asian Studies |date=15 April 2004 |accessdate=4 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080908080813/http://www.eias.org/luncheons/ford150404/glynfordcv.pdf |archivedate=8 September 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Academic career==\nFor most of his academic career Ford worked at the [[University of Manchester]], as a [[research fellow]] (1976\u20131979), a lecturer (1979\u20131980), and finally as a senior research fellow in the Department of Science and Technology Policy (1980\u20131984).<ref name=debretts/><ref name=eias-cv/>\n\nHe also taught for the [[Open University]] (1976\u20131978) and [[University of Manchester Institute of Science and Technology|UMIST]] (1977\u20131978). He was a research fellow at the [[University of Sussex]] (1978\u20131979). In 1983, he spent six months as a visiting professor at [[Tokyo University]].<ref name=debretts/><ref name=eias-cv/>\n\nAfter becoming a member of the European Parliament in 1984, the University of Manchester made him an honorary visiting research fellow.<ref name=debretts/>\n\n==Political career==\nWhile working at the University he was a local councillor in the Greater Manchester borough of [[Tameside]], where he was the Chair of the Environmental Health and Education Committees.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}}\n\nOn [[1984 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|14 June 1984]] Ford was elected as a member of the European Parliament for the new constituency of [[Greater Manchester East (European Parliament constituency)|Greater Manchester East]].  He held this seat for three terms, until the constituency was abolished in 1999, being re-elected on [[1989 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|15 June 1989]] and [[1994 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|9 June 1994]].\n\nIn 1987 he stood as the Labour candidate for the [[Hazel Grove (UK Parliament constituency)|Hazel Grove constituency]] in Greater Manchester in the [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987 general election]], a seat where Labour had no likelihood of winning.<ref name=debretts/>\n\nFrom 1989 to 1993 he was a member of Labour's [[National Executive Committee]].<ref name=debretts/>\n\nAlso, from 1989 to 1993 Ford was Leader of the [[European Parliamentary Labour Party]] and Deputy Chair of the [[Progressive Alliance of Socialists and Democrats|European Parliament Socialist Group]].<ref name=debretts/>\n\nOn [[1999 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|10 June 1999]] Ford was elected as a member of the European Parliament for the constituency of [[South West England (European Parliament constituency)|South West England]] for both the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] and the [[Gibraltar Socialist Labour Party]]. [[Gibraltar]] was part of the South West England European Parliament constituency. Ford campaigned for Gibraltar to have its own seat in the European Parliament, rather than only having representation through the South West England constituency.<ref>https://www.webcitation.org/5gPXFUSBZ?url=http://www.panorama.gi/localnews/headlines.php?action=view_article&article=4381&offset=0</ref><ref>http://www.panorama.gi/localnews/headlines.php?action=view_article&article=4381&offset=0</ref>\n\nFord held this seat for two terms, being re-elected on [[2004 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|10 June 2004]]. He lost his seat in the [[2009 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|elections on 4 June 2009]].  The Labour Party gained 118,716 votes (7.61%) in the South West region in 2009, which was insufficient to win a seat in the multi-member constituency which had had its representation reduced from seven to six at that election.<ref name=europarlresult2009>\n{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.europarl.org.uk/section/european-elections/results-2009-european-elections-uk\n |title       = Results of 2009 European elections in the UK\n |publisher   = UK Office of the European Parliament\n |date        = 9 June 2009\n |accessdate  = 2009-06-09\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090607204700/http://www.europarl.org.uk/section/european-elections/results-2009-european-elections-uk\n |archivedate = 7 June 2009\n}}\n</ref>\n\nFord's three main areas of interest are Research and Development, Racism and East Asia.<ref name=labour-npf>{{cite web |url=http://www.yourbritain.org.uk/agenda-2015/npf-representatives/glyn-ford |title=Glyn Ford |work=Your Britain |publisher=Labour |accessdate=21 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140722220807/http://www.yourbritain.org.uk/agenda-2015/npf-representatives/glyn-ford |archivedate=22 July 2014 }}</ref> Ford was for fifteen years a member of the European Parliament's Research Committee, the Guest Editor of the Science and Public Policy Special Issue on Science and Technology in Europe and the author, with Chris Niblett and Lindsay Walker, of ''The Future for Ocean Technology'' (Frances Pinter, 1987).\n\nFord was Chair of the European Parliament's Committee of Inquiry into The Growth of Racism and Fascism in Europe (1984\u201386) and ''rapporteur'' for a second European Parliament Committee of Inquiry into Racism and Xenophobia. He served as the European Parliament's representative on the Council of Ministers Consultative Commission on Racism and Xenophobia (1994\u201399). He was National Treasurer of the [[Anti-Nazi League]]<ref name=labour-npf/> and author of Fascist Europe (Pluto, 1992).\n\nHe served throughout his time in the European Parliament as a member of the Japan Delegation and as a member of the Korean Peninsula Delegation from its formation in 2004. He was the EU's Chief Election Observer in Indonesia in 2004 and Aceh 2006\u20137. In 2008, he published, ''North Korea on the Brink: Struggle for Survival'' (Pluto) which has been subsequently been published in Japanese and Korean. He writes for [[The Japan Times]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/author/int-glyn_ford/ |title=Glyn Ford |newspaper=The Japan Times |accessdate=21 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe published with [[Glenys Kinnock]] and [[Arlene McCarthy]] ''Changing States: A Labour Agenda for Europe'' (Mandarin, 1996). He is a regular contributor to [[Tribune (magazine)|Tribune]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tribunemagazine.org/author/glyn-ford/ |title=All articles by: Glyn Ford |newspaper=Tribune |accessdate=21 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter leaving the European Parliament, Ford founded the Public Affairs and International Relations consultancy POLINT.<ref name=polint-ford>{{cite web |url=http://www.pol-int.eu/i/it/about-us/glyn-ford/glyn-ford.html |title=J. Glyn Ford |publisher=POLINT |accessdate=15 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nFord stood in the [[2014 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2014 European Parliament election]], but his second position on the Labour [[South West England (European Parliament constituency)|South West England]] list did not yield a seat.\n\nFord is a member of the Labour Party [[National Policy Forum]], and was re-elected in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://labourlist.org/2012/06/national-policy-forum-the-results/ |title=National Policy Forum \u2013 the results |publisher=LabourList |date=20 June 2012 |accessdate=14 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.labour.org.uk/blog/entry/results-of-elections-to-the-national-policy-forum-and-conference-arrangemen |title=Results of elections to the National Policy Forum and Conference Arrangements Committee |publisher=Labour Party |date=14 September 2015 |accessdate=14 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151018155131/http://www.labour.org.uk/blog/entry/results-of-elections-to-the-national-policy-forum-and-conference-arrangemen |archivedate=18 October 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book |title=Ocean thermal energy : prospects and opportunities |author1=Glyn Ford |author2=Chris A Niblett |author3=Lindsay Walker |publisher=Manchester University |year=1981 |oclc=12472220}}\n*{{cite book |title=The Future for Ocean Technology (The Future for Science and Technology Series) |author1=Glyn Ford |author2=Chris A Niblett |author3=Lindsay Walker |publisher=Continuum International Publishing |year=1987 |isbn=978-0861875221 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/futureforoceante0000ford }}\n*{{cite book |title=Fascist Europe : the rise of racism and xenophobia |url=https://archive.org/details/fascisteurope00glyn |url-access=registration |author=Glyn Ford |publisher=Pluto Press |year=1992 |isbn=978-0745306681}}\n*{{cite book |title=North Korea on the Brink: Struggle For Survival |author1=Glyn Ford |author2=Soyoung Kwon |publisher=Pluto Press |year=2007 |isbn=978-0745325996}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140504205318/http://glynford.org/ Official website]\n*{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100505052456/http://www.glynford.com/ |date=5 May 2010 |title=Official website }}\n*[http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/1413/GLYN_FORD_home.html profile at European Parliament website]\n*{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080108164834/http://www.europarl.europa.eu/members/public/geoSearch/view.do?country=GB&partNumber=1&zone=South+West&language=EN&id=1413 |date=8 January 2008 |title=Glyn FORD }}, profile at European Parliament website\n\n{{start box}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box|title=Leader of the [[European Parliamentary Labour Party]]|years=1989\u20131993|before=[[Barry Seal (politician)|Barry Seal]]|after=[[Pauline Green]]}}\n{{end box}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ford, Glyn}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Reading]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College London]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MEPs]]\n[[Category:Members of the European Parliament for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 1984\u20131989]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 1989\u20131994]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 1994\u20131999]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 1999\u20132004]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 2004\u20132009]]\n[[Category:People educated at Marling School]]\n[[Category:People from Gloucester]]\n[[Category:People from Stroud]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Tameside]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) parliamentary candidates]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox MEP\n| image=\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Glyn Ford\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]]\n| constituency_MP = [[South West England (European Parliament constituency)|South West England]]\n| parliament = European\n| majority =\n| predecessor = ''[[European Parliamentary Elections Act 1999|Constituency established]]''\n| successor = ''Seat abolished''\n| term_start = 1 May 1999\n| term_end = 14 July 2009\n| office2 = Leader <br> [[European Parliamentary Labour Party]]\n| parliament2 = \n| term_start2 = 1989\n| term_end2 = 1993\n| majority2 =\n| predecessor2 =\n| successor2 =\n| office3 = Member of the European Parliament <br> for [[Greater Manchester East (European Parliament constituency)|Greater Manchester East]]\n| parliament3 = \n| term_start3 = 14 June 1984\n| term_end3 = 10 June 1999\n| majority3 =\n| predecessor3 = ''Constituency established''\n| successor3 = ''Constituency abolished''\n|office4     = Member of [[Tameside (borough)|Tameside Borough Council]]\n|term_start4 = ?\n|term_end4  = ?\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1950|01|28|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Gloucester]], England, United Kingdom\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| spouse =\n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[University of Reading]]<br>[[University College London]]\n| occupation =\n| profession = Academic\n| religion =\n| signature =\n| website = [https://web.archive.org/web/20140504205318/http://glynford.org/ glynford.org]\n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''Glyn Ford''' (born 28 January 1950) is a former [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] [[member of the European Parliament]] (1984\u20132009), initially for [[Greater Manchester East (European Parliament constituency)|Greater Manchester East]] until 1999, then [[South West England (European Parliament constituency)|South West England]] from 1999 to 2009.<ref name=ep-profile>{{cite web |url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/1413/GLYN_FORD_home.html |title=Glyn FORD |publisher=European Parliament |accessdate=4 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nFord was born in [[Gloucester]].<ref name=ep-profile/> He went to [[Marling School]], [[Stroud]]. After a year as an apprentice at the [[British Aircraft Corporation]] he returned to education gaining a degree in Geology from the [[University of Reading]] in 1972, then a master's degree in marine Earth science from [[University College London]] in 1974.<ref name=debretts>{{cite web |url=http://www.debretts.com/people-of-today/profile/17473/%28James%29-Glyn-FORD |title=(James) Glyn FORD |publisher=Debretts |work=People of Today |accessdate=4 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923230908/http://www.debretts.com/people-of-today/profile/17473/%28James%29-Glyn-FORD |archivedate=23 September 2015 }}</ref><ref name=eias-cv>{{cite web |url=http://www.eias.org/luncheons/ford150404/glynfordcv.pdf |title=Mr. Glyn Ford MEP: Brief CV |publisher=European Institute for Asian Studies |date=15 April 2004 |accessdate=4 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080908080813/http://www.eias.org/luncheons/ford150404/glynfordcv.pdf |archivedate=8 September 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Academic career==\nFor most of his academic career Ford worked at the [[University of Manchester]], as a [[research fellow]] (1976\u20131979), a lecturer (1979\u20131980), and finally as a senior research fellow in the Department of Science and Technology Policy (1980\u20131984).<ref name=debretts/><ref name=eias-cv/>\n\nHe also taught for the [[Open University]] (1976\u20131978) and [[University of Manchester Institute of Science and Technology|UMIST]] (1977\u20131978). He was a research fellow at the [[University of Sussex]] (1978\u20131979). In 1983, he spent six months as a visiting professor at [[Tokyo University]].<ref name=debretts/><ref name=eias-cv/>\n\nAfter becoming a member of the European Parliament in 1984, the University of Manchester made him an honorary visiting research fellow.<ref name=debretts/>\n\n==Political career==\nWhile working at the University he was a local councillor in the Greater Manchester borough of [[Tameside]], where he was the Chair of the Environmental Health and Education Committees.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}}\n\nOn [[1984 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|14 June 1984]] Ford was elected as a member of the European Parliament for the new constituency of [[Greater Manchester East (European Parliament constituency)|Greater Manchester East]].  He held this seat for three terms, until the constituency was abolished in 1999, being re-elected on [[1989 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|15 June 1989]] and [[1994 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|9 June 1994]].\n\nIn 1987 he stood as the Labour candidate for the [[Hazel Grove (UK Parliament constituency)|Hazel Grove constituency]] in Greater Manchester in the [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987 general election]], a seat where Labour had no likelihood of winning.<ref name=debretts/>\n\nFrom 1989 to 1993 he was a member of Labour's [[National Executive Committee]].<ref name=debretts/>\n\nAlso, from 1989 to 1993 Ford was Leader of the [[European Parliamentary Labour Party]] and Deputy Chair of the [[Progressive Alliance of Socialists and Democrats|European Parliament Socialist Group]].<ref name=debretts/>\n\nOn [[1999 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|10 June 1999]] Ford was elected as a member of the European Parliament for the constituency of [[South West England (European Parliament constituency)|South West England]] for both the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] and the [[Gibraltar Socialist Labour Party]]. [[Gibraltar]] was part of the South West England European Parliament constituency. Ford campaigned for Gibraltar to have its own seat in the European Parliament, rather than only having representation through the South West England constituency.<ref>https://www.webcitation.org/5gPXFUSBZ?url=http://www.panorama.gi/localnews/headlines.php?action=view_article&article=4381&offset=0</ref><ref>http://www.panorama.gi/localnews/headlines.php?action=view_article&article=4381&offset=0</ref>\n\nFord held this seat for two terms, being re-elected on [[2004 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|10 June 2004]]. He lost his seat in the [[2009 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|elections on 4 June 2009]].  The Labour Party gained 118,716 votes (7.61%) in the South West region in 2009, which was insufficient to win a seat in the multi-member constituency which had had its representation reduced from seven to six at that election.<ref name=europarlresult2009>\n{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.europarl.org.uk/section/european-elections/results-2009-european-elections-uk\n |title       = Results of 2009 European elections in the UK\n |publisher   = UK Office of the European Parliament\n |date        = 9 June 2009\n |accessdate  = 2009-06-09\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090607204700/http://www.europarl.org.uk/section/european-elections/results-2009-european-elections-uk\n |archivedate = 7 June 2009\n}}\n</ref>\n\nFord's three main areas of interest are Research and Development, Racism and East Asia.<ref name=labour-npf>{{cite web |url=http://www.yourbritain.org.uk/agenda-2015/npf-representatives/glyn-ford |title=Glyn Ford |work=Your Britain |publisher=Labour |accessdate=21 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140722220807/http://www.yourbritain.org.uk/agenda-2015/npf-representatives/glyn-ford |archivedate=22 July 2014 }}</ref> Ford was for fifteen years a member of the European Parliament's Research Committee, the Guest Editor of the Science and Public Policy Special Issue on Science and Technology in Europe and the author, with Chris Niblett and Lindsay Walker, of ''The Future for Ocean Technology'' (Frances Pinter, 1987).\n\nFord was Chair of the European Parliament's Committee of Inquiry into The Growth of Racism and Fascism in Europe (1984\u201386) and ''rapporteur'' for a second European Parliament Committee of Inquiry into Racism and Xenophobia. He served as the European Parliament's representative on the Council of Ministers Consultative Commission on Racism and Xenophobia (1994\u201399). He was National Treasurer of the [[Anti-Nazi League]]<ref name=labour-npf/> and author of Fascist Europe (Pluto, 1992).\n\nHe served throughout his time in the European Parliament as a member of the Japan Delegation and as a member of the Korean Peninsula Delegation from its formation in 2004. He was the EU's Chief Election Observer in Indonesia in 2004 and Aceh 2006-7. In 2008, he published, ''North Korea on the Brink: Struggle for Survival'' (Pluto) which has been subsequently been published in Japanese and Korean. He writes for [[The Japan Times]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/author/int-glyn_ford/ |title=Glyn Ford |newspaper=The Japan Times |accessdate=21 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe published with [[Glenys Kinnock]] and [[Arlene McCarthy]] ''Changing States: A Labour Agenda for Europe'' (Mandarin, 1996). He is a regular contributor to [[Tribune (magazine)|Tribune]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tribunemagazine.org/author/glyn-ford/ |title=All articles by: Glyn Ford |newspaper=Tribune |accessdate=21 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter leaving the European Parliament, Ford founded the Public Affairs and International Relations consultancy POLINT.<ref name=polint-ford>{{cite web |url=http://www.pol-int.eu/i/it/about-us/glyn-ford/glyn-ford.html |title=J. Glyn Ford |publisher=POLINT |accessdate=15 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nFord stood in the [[2014 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2014 European Parliament election]], but his second position on the Labour [[South West England (European Parliament constituency)|South West England]] list did not yield a seat.\n\nFord is a member of the Labour Party [[National Policy Forum]], and was re-elected in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://labourlist.org/2012/06/national-policy-forum-the-results/ |title=National Policy Forum \u2013 the results |publisher=LabourList |date=20 June 2012 |accessdate=14 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.labour.org.uk/blog/entry/results-of-elections-to-the-national-policy-forum-and-conference-arrangemen |title=Results of elections to the National Policy Forum and Conference Arrangements Committee |publisher=Labour Party |date=14 September 2015 |accessdate=14 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151018155131/http://www.labour.org.uk/blog/entry/results-of-elections-to-the-national-policy-forum-and-conference-arrangemen |archivedate=18 October 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book |title=Ocean thermal energy : prospects and opportunities |author1=Glyn Ford |author2=Chris A Niblett |author3=Lindsay Walker |publisher=Manchester University |year=1981 |oclc=12472220}}\n*{{cite book |title=The Future for Ocean Technology (The Future for Science and Technology Series) |author1=Glyn Ford |author2=Chris A Niblett |author3=Lindsay Walker |publisher=Continuum International Publishing |year=1987 |isbn=978-0861875221 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/futureforoceante0000ford }}\n*{{cite book |title=Fascist Europe : the rise of racism and xenophobia |url=https://archive.org/details/fascisteurope00glyn |url-access=registration |author=Glyn Ford |publisher=Pluto Press |year=1992 |isbn=978-0745306681}}\n*{{cite book |title=North Korea on the Brink: Struggle For Survival |author1=Glyn Ford |author2=Soyoung Kwon |publisher=Pluto Press |year=2007 |isbn=978-0745325996}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140504205318/http://glynford.org/ Official website]\n*{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100505052456/http://www.glynford.com/ |date=5 May 2010 |title=Official website }}\n*[http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/1413/GLYN_FORD_home.html profile at European Parliament website]\n*{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080108164834/http://www.europarl.europa.eu/members/public/geoSearch/view.do?country=GB&partNumber=1&zone=South+West&language=EN&id=1413 |date=8 January 2008 |title=Glyn FORD }}, profile at European Parliament website\n\n{{start box}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box|title=Leader of the [[European Parliamentary Labour Party]]|years=1989\u20131993|before=[[Barry Seal (politician)|Barry Seal]]|after=[[Pauline Green]]}}\n{{end box}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ford, Glyn}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Reading]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College London]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MEPs]]\n[[Category:Members of the European Parliament for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 1984\u20131989]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 1989\u20131994]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 1994\u20131999]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 1999\u20132004]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 2004\u20132009]]\n[[Category:People educated at Marling School]]\n[[Category:People from Gloucester]]\n[[Category:People from Stroud]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Tameside]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) parliamentary candidates]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePolitical career:clean up,typo(s) fixed: 2006-7 \u2192 2006\u20137", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glyn_Ford"}
{"title_page": "Edward Baron Turk", "text_new": "{{Infobox academic\n| honorific_prefix   =\n| name               = Edward Baron Turk\n| honorific_suffix   =\n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| image              = Edward Baron Turk.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = <!-- Use only if different from full/othernames -->\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1946|09|29}}\n| birth_place        = Brooklyn, New York\n| death_date         = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> \n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| region             =\n| nationality        = [[United States|USA]]\n| period             = \n| occupation         = \n| title              = \n| boards             = <!-- Board or similar positions extraneous to main occupation   -->\n| known_for          =\n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n| signature_size     = \n| era                =\n\n| discipline         = <!-- Major academic discipline - e.g. Physicist, Sociologist, New Testament scholar, Ancient Near Eastern Linguist -->\n| sub_discipline     = <!-- Academic discipline specialist area - e.g. Sub-atomic research, 20th Century Danish specialist, Pauline research, Arcadian and Ugaritic specialist -->\n| movement           = <!-- Should match the idiologial movement or denomination (for religious), \"school\" of thought etc. (e.g. \"Anglican\", \"Postmodernist\", \"Socialist\" or \"Green\" etc. -->\n| religion           = <!-- Religion should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| denomination       = <!-- Religious denomination should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = <!-- will often consist of the linked name of the last-attended higher education institution. -->\n| thesis_title       = \n| thesis_url         = \n| thesis_year        = \n| doctoral_advisor   = \n| doctoral_students  = \n| notable_students   = <!--Only those with WP articles-->\n| main_interests     = \n| workplaces         = <!--full-time positions only, not student positions-->\n| notable_works      = \n| notable_ideas      = \n| influences         = <!--Must be referenced from a third party source-->\n| influenced         = <!--Must be referenced from a third party source-->\n| awards             = Chevalier in the [[Ordre des Arts et des Lettres|Order of Arts and Letters]] (France, 1995)<br/>Officier in the Order of Academic Palms (France, 2013) <!--Notable national level awards only-->\n| website            = http://web.mit.edu/ebturk/\n| footnotes          =\n}}\n\n'''Edward Baron Turk''' (born September 29, 1946)<ref>{{cite web\n|url= http://web.mit.edu/ebturk/ |title=Edward Baron Turk  |work=MIT Homepages |accessdate=March 27, 2016}}</ref> is a multiple prize-winning American author, arts critic, and educator.  He has held professorial positions at [[Yale University]], the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (MIT), [[Columbia University]] (School of the Arts), and the Institut des Etudes Politiques (\"[[Sciences Po]],\" Paris).  He writes mainly on the culture of France \u2013 especially its theatre, cinema, and literature \u2013 and on Hollywood film. As an author, he has been largely collected by libraries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n77017502/ |title=Turk, Edward Baron |publisher=worldcat.org |accessdate=November 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1973, Yale University appointed Turk as Assistant Professor and Director of Undergraduate Studies in French.  In 1978 he joined the humanities faculty of MIT as an Associate Professor of French and Film Studies, and from 1982 to 1985 he headed MIT's Foreign Languages and Literatures Section (the programs in French, German, Russian, Spanish, and English as a Second Language).  At MIT, where he was promoted to Full Professor in 1990, Turk was a principal architect of the Ivy League-MIT-University of Chicago-Stanford University Consortium on Language and Teaching and of the MIT graduate program in Comparative Media Studies.  In 2005 he was awarded an endowed MIT chair, the John E. Burchard Professorship of the Humanities.\n\nTurk retired from MIT in June 2012.  As part of a public celebration honoring his career in October 2011, he delivered a talk titled \"Valedictory Thoughts of an MIT Humanist,\" in which he described the importance of a deep engagement with the liberal arts in light of the increasingly market-driven turn of pre-professional undergraduate education.  (See http://shass.mit.edu/news/news-2012-edward-turk-valedictory-thoughts-mit-humanist)\n\nSince leaving [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]], Turk has continued with his research and writing, and has been regularly teaching seminars in film studies in the Film Division of Columbia University School of the Arts.\n\n==Books==\n* ''Baroque Fiction-Making'', University of North Carolina Press (1978), {{ISBN|978-0-80789-196-4}}.\n* ''Child of Paradise: Marcel Carn\u00e9 and the Golden Age of French Cinema'', Harvard University Press (1989), {{ISBN|978-0-67411-460-9}}.\n* ''Hollywood Diva: A Biography of Jeanette MacDonald'', University of California Press (1998), {{ISBN|978-0-52021-202-2}}.\n* ''Marcel Carn\u00e9 et l'\u00e2ge d'or du cin\u00e9ma fran\u00e7ais,'' L'Harmattan [Paris] (2003), {{ISBN|978-2-74752-492-6}}.\n* ''French Theater Today'': ''The View from New York, Paris, and Avignon,'' University of Iowa Press (2011), {{ISBN|978-1-58729-992-6}}.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Other Writings ==\nTurk's writings on the arts have appeared in such mainstream publications as ''Architectural Digest'', ''American Film,'' ''Film Quarterly'', and the ''San Francisco Chronicle''.   His scholarly articles have been published in numerous academic journals, including ''Philosophy and Rhetoric'', ''Cinema Journal'', ''Literature/Film Quarterly'', ''Camera Obscura'', ''Iris'', ''The French Review'',and ''Modern Language Studies''.  For many years he was the Assistant Editor for film at ''The French Review'', the scholarly journal of the American Association of Teachers of French.  From 2006 through 2013, he wrote in-depth chronicles of the Avignon Theatre Festival for each October issue ''of The French Review''.\n\n== Honors and Prizes ==\n1990.  Prize, Theatre Library Association, for the book ''Child of Paradise'' <ref>{{cite web\n|url= http://www.tla-online.org/awards/bookawards/wall-award-winners/ |title=Theatre Library Association Prize notice  |accessdate=April 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n1993-1998.  President, Xi chapter (Massachusetts Institute of Technology), [[Phi Beta Kappa]] Society\n\n1995. Awarded insignia by France's Ministry of Culture as ''Chevalier de l'Ordre des Arts et des Lettres''\n\n1998. Selected, author of \"one of the best books of 1998\" by the ''Philadelphia Inquirer'' for ''Hollywood Diva'' <ref>{{cite web\n|url= https://news.mit.edu/1999/artnews-0113 |title=Philadelphia Inquirer award notice |accessdate=April 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n1999.  Finalist, Kurt Weill Foundation Book Prize, for ''Hollywood Diva'' <ref>{{cite web\n|url= http://www.kwf.org/pages/pr-1999-kurt-weill-prizes-presented-for-distinguished-scholarship-in-music-theater.html |title=Kurt Weill Book Prize notice |accessdate=April 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n2002.  Prize, Le Prix du Syndicat de la Critique du cin\u00e9ma pour le meilleur livre \u00e9tranger [French Film Critics Association Prize for best book of the year by a foreign author].\n\n2013. Awarded insignia by France's Ministry of Education as ''Officier de l'Ordre des Palmes Acad\u00e9miques''\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://web.mit.edu/ebturk/ Edward Baron Turk's website] at MIT\n* [http://shass.mit.edu/news/news-2012-edward-turk-valedictory-thoughts-mit-humanist shass.mit.edu/news/news-2012-edward-turk-valedictory-thoughts-mit-humanist]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Turk, Edward Baron}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology faculty]]\n[[Category:Columbia University faculty]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:Chevaliers of the Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]]\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Writers from Brooklyn]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox academic\n| honorific_prefix   =\n| name               = Edward Baron Turk\n| honorific_suffix   =\n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| image              = Edward Baron Turk.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = <!-- Use only if different from full/othernames -->\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1946|09|29}}\n| birth_place        = Brooklyn, New York\n| death_date         = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> \n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| region             =\n| nationality        = [[United States|USA]]\n| period             = \n| occupation         = \n| title              = \n| boards             = <!-- Board or similar positions extraneous to main occupation   -->\n| known_for          =\n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n| signature_size     = \n| era                =\n\n| discipline         = <!-- Major academic discipline - e.g. Physicist, Sociologist, New Testament scholar, Ancient Near Eastern Linguist -->\n| sub_discipline     = <!-- Academic discipline specialist area - e.g. Sub-atomic research, 20th Century Danish specialist, Pauline research, Arcadian and Ugaritic specialist -->\n| movement           = <!-- Should match the idiologial movement or denomination (for religious), \"school\" of thought etc. (e.g. \"Anglican\", \"Postmodernist\", \"Socialist\" or \"Green\" etc. -->\n| religion 