[1999 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|1999]]\u2013[[Brexit|2020]]\n}}\n{{s-non\n| reason = Constituency abolished\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Brexit Party}}\n{{UKIP}}\n{{Fox News personalities}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Farage, Nigel}}\n[[Category:Nigel Farage|*]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Anglicans]]\n[[Category:21st-century Anglicans]]\n[[Category:Brexit]]\n[[Category:Climate change denial]]\n[[Category:Conservatism in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Critics of the European Union]]\n[[Category:Critics of Islamism]]\n[[Category:Critics of multiculturalism]]\n[[Category:Drug policy reform activists]]\n[[Category:English Anglicans]]\n[[Category:English autobiographers]]\n[[Category:English commodities traders]]\n[[Category:English libertarians]]\n[[Category:English people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the UK Independence Party]]\n[[Category:Members of the European Parliament for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 1999\u20132004]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 2004\u20132009]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 2009\u20132014]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 2014\u20132019]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 2019\u20132020]]\n[[Category:People associated with Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]]\n[[Category:People educated at Dulwich College]]\n[[Category:People from Bromley]]\n[[Category:Survivors of aviation accidents or incidents]]\n[[Category:Testicular cancer survivors]]\n[[Category:UK Independence Party MEPs]]\n[[Category:Brexit Party MEPs]]\n[[Category:British Eurosceptics]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e2016 referendum:clean up,typo(s) fixed: 52-48 \u2192 52\u201348", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nigel_Farage"}
{"title_page": "Two Women", "text_new": "{{About|the 1960 Italian film||Two Women (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Two Women\n| image = TwoWomenPoster.jpg\n| caption = UK [[film poster]]<!-- poster names MGM as distributor- below, MGM listed as distributor for Rest of World outside US and Italy, hence US seems unlikely- reverted to previous -->\n| director = [[Vittorio De Sica]]\n| producer = [[Carlo Ponti]]\n| writer = [[Cesare Zavattini]]<br />'''Uncredited:'''<br>Vittorio De Sica\n| based on = ''[[Two Women (novel)|Two Women]]''<br>by [[Alberto Moravia]]\n| starring = [[Sophia Loren]]<br />[[Jean-Paul Belmondo]]<br>[[Raf Vallone]]<br />[[Eleonora Brown]]\n | music = [[Armando Trovajoli]]\n | cinematography = [[G\u00e1bor Pog\u00e1ny]]\n| editing = Adriana Novelli\n| studio = Compagnia Cinematografica Champion<br>Cocinor<br>Les Films Marceau<br>Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9n\u00e9rale de Cin\u00e9matographie (S.G.C.) \n| distributor = [[Titanus Distribuzione]] {{small|(Italy)}}<br>[[Embassy Pictures]] {{small|(US)}}<br>[[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] {{small|(International)}}\n| released = {{Film date|df=y|1960|12|22}}\n| runtime = 100 minutes\n| country = Italy<br>France\n| language = Italian<br />German\n| budget = \n|gross = $3.0 million (US and Canada rentals)<ref>{{cite news|title=Tracking the Players|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=January 18, 1993|page=36}}</ref><br>2,024,049 admissions (France)<ref>{{cite|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=fr&tl=en&u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.boxofficestory.com%2Fbox-office-alain-delon-c22669761%2F39&sandbox=1|title= Box office information for Jean Paul Belmondo films|website=Box Office Story}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Two Women''''' ({{lang-it|'''La ciociara'''}} {{IPA-it|la t\u0283o\u02c8t\u0283a\u02d0ra|}}, rough literal translation \"The Woman from [[Ciociaria]]\") is a 1960 [[Cinema of Italy|Italian film]] directed by [[Vittorio De Sica]]. It tells the story of a woman trying to protect her young daughter from the horrors of war. The film stars [[Sophia Loren]], [[Jean-Paul Belmondo]], [[Raf Vallone]], [[Eleonora Brown]], [[Carlo Ninchi]], and [[Andrea Checchi]]. The film was adapted by De Sica and [[Cesare Zavattini]] from the [[Two women (novel)|novel of the same name]] written by [[Alberto Moravia]]. The story is fictional, but based on actual events of July 1944 in Rome and rural [[Lazio]], during what Italians call the ''[[Marocchinate]]''.<ref>[http://www.cassino2000.com/cdsc/studi/archivio/n07/n07p09.html 1952: Il caso delle \u201cmarocchinate\u201d al Parlamento] Accessed 9 December 2017</ref>\n\nLoren's performance received critical acclaim, winning her the [[Academy Award for Best Actress]] among other accolades.\n\n==Plot==\nCesira (Loren) is a widowed shopkeeper, raising her devoutly religious twelve-year-old daughter, Rosetta (Brown), in Rome during [[World War II]]. In July 1943, following the [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] [[Bombing of Rome in World War II#July 19, 1943|bombing of Rome]], mother and daughter flee to Cesira's native [[Ciociaria]], a rural, mountainous province of central Italy. The night before they go, Cesira sleeps with Giovanni (Vallone), a coal dealer in her neighbourhood, who agrees to look after her store in her absence.\n\nAfter they arrive at Ciociaria, Cesira attracts the attention of Michele (Belmondo), a young local intellectual with [[communist]] sympathies. Rosetta sees Michele as a father figure and develops a strong bond with him. Michele is later taken prisoner by [[Wehrmacht|German soldiers]], who force him to act as a guide through the mountainous terrain.\n\nAfter the Allies capture Rome, in June 1944, Cesira and Rosetta decide to head back to that city. On the way, the two are gang-raped inside a church by a group of ''[[Moroccan Goumier]]s'' &ndash; soldiers attached to the invading [[Allied Armies in Italy]]. Rosetta is traumatized, becoming detached and distant from her mother and no longer an innocent child.\n\nWhen the two manage to find shelter at a neighbouring village, Rosetta disappears during the night, sending Cesira into a panic. She thinks Rosetta has gone to look for Michele, but later finds out that Michele was killed by the Germans. Rosetta returns, having been out with an older boy, who has given her silk stockings, despite her youth. Cesira is outraged and upset, slapping and spanking Rosetta for her behavior, but Rosetta remains unresponsive, emotionally distant. When Cesira informs Rosetta of Michele's death, Rosetta begins to cry like the little girl she had been prior to the rape. The film ends with Cesira comforting the child.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Sophia Loren]] as Cesira\n* [[Jean-Paul Belmondo]] as Michele Di Libero\n* [[Eleonora Brown]] as Rosetta\n* [[Carlo Ninchi]] as Filippo, Michele's father\n* [[Raf Vallone]] as Giovanni\n* [[Andrea Checchi]] as A fascist\n* [[Pupella Maggio]] as Peasant\n* Bruna Cealti as Refugee\n* Antonella Della Porta as A crazy mother\n* Mario Frera\n* [[Franco Balducci]] as German in the haystack\n* Luciana Cortellesi\n* [[Curt Lowens]]\n* Tony Calio\n* Remo Galavotti\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\nThe film was based on a 1957 novel by [[Alberto Moravia]], ''La ciociara'' (''The Woman From Ciociaria''). It was inspired by Moravia's experiences during World War II.\n\n[[Carlo Ponti]] bought the film rights along with Marcello Girosi for a reported US$100,000. Sophia Loren was always meant to star and there was some talk that the film might be financed by Paramount, with whom Loren had made a number of movies.<ref>{{cite news|title=JAPANESE MOVIE WILL BE ADAPTED: Alciona, U. S. Concern, to Make 'Magnificent 7' -- Moravia Novel Eyed|first=Thomas|last=Pryor|newspaper=New York Times|date=13 May 1958|page= 26}}</ref> [[Anna Magnani]] was going to play the lead and Loren was going to be her daughter. [[George Cukor]] was going to direct as part of a two-picture deal with Ponti, the other one being ''[[Heller in Pink Tights]]'' (1960).<ref>{{cite news|title=FILM EVENTS: Cukor to Direct Loren|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=4 June 1958|page= C8}}</ref> The film was going to be shot as part of a six-picture deal between Ponti and Paramount.<ref>{{cite news|title=PRODUCERS PLAN 6 PICTURES BY '61: Ponti and Girosi Will Work With Paramount -- Studio Plans Consolidation|first=Thomas|last=Pryor|newspaper=New York Times|date=6 February 1959|page= 21}}</ref> \n\nCukor and Paramount dropped out. Vittorio De Sica became attached as director. Magnani pulled out, supposedly because she did not want to play Loren's mother, leading to Loren taking Magnani's role, even though the former was only 26 at the time.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4QhnLOpcLfcC&pg=PA77&lpg=PA77&dq=two+women+film+sophia+loren&source=bl&ots=MFIgxGKCYt&sig=icLi59fPVX-yzZzm_cITzdzotlc&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiA9ZDOvbTPAhWDFZQKHXcMBY84ChDoAQhUMA0#v=onepage&q=two%20women%20film%20sophia%20loren&f=false|page=77|title=Sophia Loren: Moulding the Star|first=Pauline|last= Small|publisher=Intellect Books|year=2009}}</ref> However, De Sica says it was his decision for Loren to play Magnani's role and cast a younger performer as the daughter \"for great poignancy. If, in doing this, we moved away from original line of Moravia, we had better opportunity to stress, to underline, the monstrous impact of war on people. The historical truth is that the great majority of those raped were young girls.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=De Sica Would Dig for 'Deepest Layer': Ace 'Two Women' Director Says Realism Still Dominant|last=Scheuer|first= Philip K.|newspaper= Los Angeles Times|date=27 Nov 1961|page= C15}}</ref> In a 2017 interview, Brown stated that Loren protected her from some of the underlying implications of the rape scene in the film, and also stated that director De Sica brought her to tears for the climatic final scene of hearing that Belmondo's character has died, by saying that a telegram had arrived saying that Brown's parents had died in an accident.<ref name=BrownReturns>{{cite news |url=http://www.ilgiornale.it/news/spettacoli/piccola-ciociara-torna-cinema-1459511.html |title=La piccola \"Ciociara\" torna al cinema |first=Paolo |last=Scotti |work=[[Il Giornale]] |date=2017-11-04 |accessdate=2018-02-25}}</ref>\n\nMagnani said she was going to do it, \"Moravia wanted me, but Ponti got it, and Moravia did not fight. After that, they went through all the roles I'd turned down for Sophia Loren to play.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=In the Beginning There Was Magnani. Then Came Loren. 'Ecco!'|first=Mark|last=Shivasrome|newspaper=New York Times |date=29 Sep 1968|page= D17}}</ref> \"The book was one of the most beautiful I've ever read\", said Loren. \"I thought it was worth taking the risk at 25 to play an older woman because the story was so beautiful.\"<ref name=\"desire\">{{cite news|title=Positively Sophia: Sophia Loren talks about movies, her husband and children, being 40, and the power of positive thinking|first=Karin|last= von Faber|newspaper= Chicago Tribune|date=27 Oct 1974|page= h56}}</ref> \nLoren later said her performance was inspired by her memories of her mother during the war.<ref>{{cite news|title=The actress wins an Oscar--and a name|newspaper=Chicago Tribune |date=21 March 1979|page= b1}}</ref> She also said she was greatly helped by her experience acting in ''[[Desire Under the Elms (film)|Desire Under the Elms]]'' (1958).<ref name=\"desire\"/>\n\nPonti raised money from France and Italy. French investment was conditional upon a French star being used, which lead to the casting of [[Jean Paul Belmondo]], who had leapt to international fame in ''Breathless'' (1960). Belmondo's voice was dubbed into Italian.\n\n==Release==\nJoseph E. Levine agreed to buy US release rights after watching only nine minutes of the film.<ref>{{cite news|title=MOVIE PRODUCER SELLS THE PUBLIC: Joseph E. Levine Believes in Extravagant Openings|first=Murray|last=Schumach|newspaper=New York Times|date=9 Nov 1961|page= 39}}</ref> \"I bet Sophia she'd win the Oscar and I nursed that film like a baby\", Levine later said.<ref name=\"joe\">{{cite news|title=Self-Made Mogul Hangs On: Joseph E. Levine, 82, Is Still Wheeling and Dealing|last=Rosenthal|first= Donna|newspaper= Los Angeles Times|date=5 July 1987|page= K23}}</ref> He showed the film in every city that a member of the Academy jury lived and promoted it assiduously. \"That showed foreign films could get big audiences if promoted with flair\", said Levine.<ref name=\"joe\"/>\n\nThe movie was among the 30 most popular films at the French box office that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=fr&tl=en&u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.boxofficestory.com%2Fbox-office-alain-delon-c22669761%2F39&sandbox=1|title=1961 Box Office|website=Box Office Story}}</ref>\n\n== Recognitions ==\n* '''[[34th Academy Awards|1962 Academy Awards]]'''\n** ('''Won''') [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] to [[Sophia Loren]]\n* '''[[15th British Academy Film Awards|1962 British Academy of Film and Television Arts Awards]]'''\n** ('''Won''') [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role|Best Film Actress in a Leading Role]] to [[Sophia Loren]]\n* '''[[19th Golden Globe Awards|1962 Golden Globe Awards]]'''\n** ('''Won''') [[Golden Globe Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Foreign Language]] ([[Italy]])\n* '''[[1961 Cannes Film Festival]]'''\n** (Nominated) [[Golden Palm|Golden Palm Award for Best Film]] to [[Vittorio De Sica]] \n** ('''Won''') [[Cannes Film Festival Award for Best Actress|Best Actress Award (Prix d'interpr\u00e9tation f\u00e9minine)]] to [[Sophia Loren]]\n* '''[[1960 in film|1961 David di Donatello Awards]]'''\n** ('''Won''') [[David di Donatello for Best Actress|Best Actress in a Leading Role]] to [[Sophia Loren]]\n* '''[[Nastri d'argento|1961 Silver Ribbons Awards]]'''\n** ('''Won''') [[Nastri d'argento|Best Leading Actress]] to [[Sophia Loren]]\n* '''[[1961 New York Film Critics Circle Awards]]'''\n** ('''Won''') [[New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Actress|Best Lead Actress]] to [[Sophia Loren]]\n* '''[[National Board of Review Awards|1961 National Board of Review Awards]]'''\n** ('''Won''') [[National Board of Review Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Top 10 Foreign Language Films of the Year]] to [[Vittorio De Sica]]\n\n====Notes====\nThe film was heavily promoted by its North American distributor, [[Joseph E. Levine]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Joseph E. Levine|date=2019-10-03|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Joseph_E._Levine&oldid=919420756|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref> This was the first time an acting Oscar had been given for a non-[[English language|English]]-speaking performance ([[Sophia Loren]], [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress Oscar]] winner), although she made the English dubbing for her role herself. Loren was too nervous to attend the ceremony and elected to stay in Rome instead. [[Greer Garson]] accepted the award on Loren's behalf.\n\n==Remakes==\n''La Ciociara'' was remade for television in 1988. It was adapted by [[Diana Gould (writer)|Diana Gould]], [[Lidia Ravera]], [[Dino Risi]], and [[Bernardino Zapponi]]. It was directed by Risi, and starred Loren, [[Robert Loggia]], Leonardo Ferrantini, Dario Ghirardi, and [[Sydney Penny]]. An opera, La Ciociara, in a re-write by scenario writer Luca Rossi, with music composed by [[Marco Tutino]], received its premiere at San Francisco Opera,<ref>[https://www.opera-online.com/en/items/productions/two-women-la-ciociara-san-francisco-opera-2015-2015 Two Women (La Ciociara) - premiered at San Francisco Opera - Composer: Marco Tutino] Accessed 9 December 2017</ref> and a European premiere at [[Teatro Lirico di Cagliari|Teatro Lirico, Cagliari]].<ref>[http://www.ansa.it/sardegna/notizie/2017/11/21/cagliari-prima-europea-de-la-ciociara_e18a40da-f97e-4e35-aee9-e644c4aff8d5.html \"Cagliari, prima europea de La Ciociara Compositore Tutino, ''una storia di cui si parla poco''\" at ansa.it/sardegna] Accessed 13 December 2017</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|La Ciociara (film)}}\n*{{IMDb title|0054749|Two Women}}\n*{{Rotten Tomatoes|two_women}}\n*[http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/99299%7C0/Two-Women.html ''Two Women''] at [[TCMDB]]\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=EE05E7DF173FE177BC4153DFB366838A679EDE Review of film] at [[New York Times]]\n*[http://www.lefilmguide.com/review/la-ciociara-1960.html Film page] at Le Film Guide\n{{Vittorio De Sica}}\n\n[[Category:Italian films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Rome]]\n[[Category:Films set in Lazio]]\n[[Category:1960 films]]\n[[Category:1960s drama films]]\n[[Category:Italian black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films about rape]]\n[[Category:Films based on Italian novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by Alberto Moravia]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Vittorio De Sica]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Actress Academy Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Carlo Ponti]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Armando Trovajoli]]\n[[Category:Italian Campaign of World War II films]]\n[[Category:Italian-language films]]\n[[Category:Italian neorealist films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Cesare Zavattini]]\n[[Category:Wartime sexual violence in World War II]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the 1960 Italian film||Two Women (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Two Women\n| image = TwoWomenPoster.jpg\n| caption = UK [[film poster]]<!-- poster names MGM as distributor- below, MGM listed as distributor for Rest of World outside US and Italy, hence US seems unlikely- reverted to previous -->\n| director = [[Vittorio De Sica]]\n| producer = [[Carlo Ponti]]\n| writer = [[Cesare Zavattini]]<br />'''Uncredited:'''<br>Vittorio De Sica\n| based on = ''[[Two Women (novel)|Two Women]]''<br>by [[Alberto Moravia]]\n| starring = [[Sophia Loren]]<br />[[Jean-Paul Belmondo]]<br>[[Raf Vallone]]<br />[[Eleonora Brown]]\n | music = [[Armando Trovajoli]]\n | cinematography = [[G\u00e1bor Pog\u00e1ny]]\n| editing = Adriana Novelli\n| studio = Compagnia Cinematografica Champion<br>Cocinor<br>Les Films Marceau<br>Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9n\u00e9rale de Cin\u00e9matographie (S.G.C.) \n| distributor = [[Titanus Distribuzione]] {{small|(Italy)}}<br>[[Embassy Pictures]] {{small|(US)}}<br>[[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] {{small|(International)}}\n| released = {{Film date|df=y|1960|12|22}}\n| runtime = 100 minutes\n| country = Italy<br>France\n| language = Italian<br />German\n| budget = \n|gross = $3.0 million (US and Canada rentals)<ref>{{cite news|title=Tracking the Players|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=January 18, 1993|page=36}}</ref><br>2,024,049 admissions (France)<ref>{{cite|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=fr&tl=en&u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.boxofficestory.com%2Fbox-office-alain-delon-c22669761%2F39&sandbox=1|title= Box office information for Jean Paul Belmondo films|website=Box Office Story}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Two Women''''' ({{lang-it|'''La ciociara'''}} {{IPA-it|la t\u0283o\u02c8t\u0283a\u02d0ra|}}, rough literal translation \"The Woman from [[Ciociaria]]\") is a 1960 [[Cinema of Italy|Italian film]] directed by [[Vittorio De Sica]]. It tells the story of a woman trying to protect her young daughter from the horrors of war. The film stars [[Sophia Loren]], [[Jean-Paul Belmondo]], [[Raf Vallone]], [[Eleonora Brown]], [[Carlo Ninchi]], and [[Andrea Checchi]]. The film was adapted by De Sica and [[Cesare Zavattini]] from the [[Two women (novel)|novel of the same name]] written by [[Alberto Moravia]]. The story is fictional, but based on actual events of July 1943 in Rome and rural [[Lazio]], during what Italians call the ''[[Marocchinate]]''.<ref>[http://www.cassino2000.com/cdsc/studi/archivio/n07/n07p09.html 1952: Il caso delle \u201cmarocchinate\u201d al Parlamento] Accessed 9 December 2017</ref>\n\nLoren's performance received critical acclaim, winning her the [[Academy Award for Best Actress]] among other accolades.\n\n==Plot==\nCesira (Loren) is a widowed shopkeeper, raising her devoutly religious twelve-year-old daughter, Rosetta (Brown), in Rome during [[World War II]]. In July 1943, following the [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] [[Bombing of Rome in World War II#July 19, 1943|bombing of Rome]], mother and daughter flee to Cesira's native [[Ciociaria]], a rural, mountainous province of central Italy. The night before they go, Cesira sleeps with Giovanni (Vallone), a coal dealer in her neighbourhood, who agrees to look after her store in her absence.\n\nAfter they arrive at Ciociaria, Cesira attracts the attention of Michele (Belmondo), a young local intellectual with [[communist]] sympathies. Rosetta sees Michele as a father figure and develops a strong bond with him. Michele is later taken prisoner by [[Wehrmacht|German soldiers]], who force him to act as a guide through the mountainous terrain.\n\nAfter the Allies capture Rome, in June 1944, Cesira and Rosetta decide to head back to that city. On the way, the two are gang-raped inside a church by a group of ''[[Moroccan Goumier]]s'' &ndash; soldiers attached to the invading [[Allied Armies in Italy]]. Rosetta is traumatized, becoming detached and distant from her mother and no longer an innocent child.\n\nWhen the two manage to find shelter at a neighbouring village, Rosetta disappears during the night, sending Cesira into a panic. She thinks Rosetta has gone to look for Michele, but later finds out that Michele was killed by the Germans. Rosetta returns, having been out with an older boy, who has given her silk stockings, despite her youth. Cesira is outraged and upset, slapping and spanking Rosetta for her behavior, but Rosetta remains unresponsive, emotionally distant. When Cesira informs Rosetta of Michele's death, Rosetta begins to cry like the little girl she had been prior to the rape. The film ends with Cesira comforting the child.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Sophia Loren]] as Cesira\n* [[Jean-Paul Belmondo]] as Michele Di Libero\n* [[Eleonora Brown]] as Rosetta\n* [[Carlo Ninchi]] as Filippo, Michele's father\n* [[Raf Vallone]] as Giovanni\n* [[Andrea Checchi]] as A fascist\n* [[Pupella Maggio]] as Peasant\n* Bruna Cealti as Refugee\n* Antonella Della Porta as A crazy mother\n* Mario Frera\n* [[Franco Balducci]] as German in the haystack\n* Luciana Cortellesi\n* [[Curt Lowens]]\n* Tony Calio\n* Remo Galavotti\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\nThe film was based on a 1957 novel by [[Alberto Moravia]], ''La ciociara'' (''The Woman From Ciociaria''). It was inspired by Moravia's experiences during World War II.\n\n[[Carlo Ponti]] bought the film rights along with Marcello Girosi for a reported US$100,000. Sophia Loren was always meant to star and there was some talk that the film might be financed by Paramount, with whom Loren had made a number of movies.<ref>{{cite news|title=JAPANESE MOVIE WILL BE ADAPTED: Alciona, U. S. Concern, to Make 'Magnificent 7' -- Moravia Novel Eyed|first=Thomas|last=Pryor|newspaper=New York Times|date=13 May 1958|page= 26}}</ref> [[Anna Magnani]] was going to play the lead and Loren was going to be her daughter. [[George Cukor]] was going to direct as part of a two-picture deal with Ponti, the other one being ''[[Heller in Pink Tights]]'' (1960).<ref>{{cite news|title=FILM EVENTS: Cukor to Direct Loren|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=4 June 1958|page= C8}}</ref> The film was going to be shot as part of a six-picture deal between Ponti and Paramount.<ref>{{cite news|title=PRODUCERS PLAN 6 PICTURES BY '61: Ponti and Girosi Will Work With Paramount -- Studio Plans Consolidation|first=Thomas|last=Pryor|newspaper=New York Times|date=6 February 1959|page= 21}}</ref> \n\nCukor and Paramount dropped out. Vittorio De Sica became attached as director. Magnani pulled out, supposedly because she did not want to play Loren's mother, leading to Loren taking Magnani's role, even though the former was only 26 at the time.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4QhnLOpcLfcC&pg=PA77&lpg=PA77&dq=two+women+film+sophia+loren&source=bl&ots=MFIgxGKCYt&sig=icLi59fPVX-yzZzm_cITzdzotlc&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiA9ZDOvbTPAhWDFZQKHXcMBY84ChDoAQhUMA0#v=onepage&q=two%20women%20film%20sophia%20loren&f=false|page=77|title=Sophia Loren: Moulding the Star|first=Pauline|last= Small|publisher=Intellect Books|year=2009}}</ref> However, De Sica says it was his decision for Loren to play Magnani's role and cast a younger performer as the daughter \"for great poignancy. If, in doing this, we moved away from original line of Moravia, we had better opportunity to stress, to underline, the monstrous impact of war on people. The historical truth is that the great majority of those raped were young girls.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=De Sica Would Dig for 'Deepest Layer': Ace 'Two Women' Director Says Realism Still Dominant|last=Scheuer|first= Philip K.|newspaper= Los Angeles Times|date=27 Nov 1961|page= C15}}</ref> In a 2017 interview, Brown stated that Loren protected her from some of the underlying implications of the rape scene in the film, and also stated that director De Sica brought her to tears for the climatic final scene of hearing that Belmondo's character has died, by saying that a telegram had arrived saying that Brown's parents had died in an accident.<ref name=BrownReturns>{{cite news |url=http://www.ilgiornale.it/news/spettacoli/piccola-ciociara-torna-cinema-1459511.html |title=La piccola \"Ciociara\" torna al cinema |first=Paolo |last=Scotti |work=[[Il Giornale]] |date=2017-11-04 |accessdate=2018-02-25}}</ref>\n\nMagnani said she was going to do it, \"Moravia wanted me, but Ponti got it, and Moravia did not fight. After that, they went through all the roles I'd turned down for Sophia Loren to play.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=In the Beginning There Was Magnani. Then Came Loren. 'Ecco!'|first=Mark|last=Shivasrome|newspaper=New York Times |date=29 Sep 1968|page= D17}}</ref> \"The book was one of the most beautiful I've ever read\", said Loren. \"I thought it was worth taking the risk at 25 to play an older woman because the story was so beautiful.\"<ref name=\"desire\">{{cite news|title=Positively Sophia: Sophia Loren talks about movies, her husband and children, being 40, and the power of positive thinking|first=Karin|last= von Faber|newspaper= Chicago Tribune|date=27 Oct 1974|page= h56}}</ref> \nLoren later said her performance was inspired by her memories of her mother during the war.<ref>{{cite news|title=The actress wins an Oscar--and a name|newspaper=Chicago Tribune |date=21 March 1979|page= b1}}</ref> She also said she was greatly helped by her experience acting in ''[[Desire Under the Elms (film)|Desire Under the Elms]]'' (1958).<ref name=\"desire\"/>\n\nPonti raised money from France and Italy. French investment was conditional upon a French star being used, which lead to the casting of [[Jean Paul Belmondo]], who had leapt to international fame in ''Breathless'' (1960). Belmondo's voice was dubbed into Italian.\n\n==Release==\nJoseph E. Levine agreed to buy US release rights after watching only nine minutes of the film.<ref>{{cite news|title=MOVIE PRODUCER SELLS THE PUBLIC: Joseph E. Levine Believes in Extravagant Openings|first=Murray|last=Schumach|newspaper=New York Times|date=9 Nov 1961|page= 39}}</ref> \"I bet Sophia she'd win the Oscar and I nursed that film like a baby\", Levine later said.<ref name=\"joe\">{{cite news|title=Self-Made Mogul Hangs On: Joseph E. Levine, 82, Is Still Wheeling and Dealing|last=Rosenthal|first= Donna|newspaper= Los Angeles Times|date=5 July 1987|page= K23}}</ref> He showed the film in every city that a member of the Academy jury lived and promoted it assiduously. \"That showed foreign films could get big audiences if promoted with flair\", said Levine.<ref name=\"joe\"/>\n\nThe movie was among the 30 most popular films at the French box office that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=fr&tl=en&u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.boxofficestory.com%2Fbox-office-alain-delon-c22669761%2F39&sandbox=1|title=1961 Box Office|website=Box Office Story}}</ref>\n\n== Recognitions ==\n* '''[[34th Academy Awards|1962 Academy Awards]]'''\n** ('''Won''') [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] to [[Sophia Loren]]\n* '''[[15th British Academy Film Awards|1962 British Academy of Film and Television Arts Awards]]'''\n** ('''Won''') [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role|Best Film Actress in a Leading Role]] to [[Sophia Loren]]\n* '''[[19th Golden Globe Awards|1962 Golden Globe Awards]]'''\n** ('''Won''') [[Golden Globe Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Foreign Language]] ([[Italy]])\n* '''[[1961 Cannes Film Festival]]'''\n** (Nominated) [[Golden Palm|Golden Palm Award for Best Film]] to [[Vittorio De Sica]] \n** ('''Won''') [[Cannes Film Festival Award for Best Actress|Best Actress Award (Prix d'interpr\u00e9tation f\u00e9minine)]] to [[Sophia Loren]]\n* '''[[1960 in film|1961 David di Donatello Awards]]'''\n** ('''Won''') [[David di Donatello for Best Actress|Best Actress in a Leading Role]] to [[Sophia Loren]]\n* '''[[Nastri d'argento|1961 Silver Ribbons Awards]]'''\n** ('''Won''') [[Nastri d'argento|Best Leading Actress]] to [[Sophia Loren]]\n* '''[[1961 New York Film Critics Circle Awards]]'''\n** ('''Won''') [[New York Film Critics Circle Award for Best Actress|Best Lead Actress]] to [[Sophia Loren]]\n* '''[[National Board of Review Awards|1961 National Board of Review Awards]]'''\n** ('''Won''') [[National Board of Review Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Top 10 Foreign Language Films of the Year]] to [[Vittorio De Sica]]\n\n====Notes====\nThe film was heavily promoted by its North American distributor, [[Joseph E. Levine]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Joseph E. Levine|date=2019-10-03|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Joseph_E._Levine&oldid=919420756|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref> This was the first time an acting Oscar had been given for a non-[[English language|English]]-speaking performance ([[Sophia Loren]], [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress Oscar]] winner), although she made the English dubbing for her role herself. Loren was too nervous to attend the ceremony and elected to stay in Rome instead. [[Greer Garson]] accepted the award on Loren's behalf.\n\n==Remakes==\n''La Ciociara'' was remade for television in 1988. It was adapted by [[Diana Gould (writer)|Diana Gould]], [[Lidia Ravera]], [[Dino Risi]], and [[Bernardino Zapponi]]. It was directed by Risi, and starred Loren, [[Robert Loggia]], Leonardo Ferrantini, Dario Ghirardi, and [[Sydney Penny]]. An opera, La Ciociara, in a re-write by scenario writer Luca Rossi, with music composed by [[Marco Tutino]], received its premiere at San Francisco Opera,<ref>[https://www.opera-online.com/en/items/productions/two-women-la-ciociara-san-francisco-opera-2015-2015 Two Women (La Ciociara) - premiered at San Francisco Opera - Composer: Marco Tutino] Accessed 9 December 2017</ref> and a European premiere at [[Teatro Lirico di Cagliari|Teatro Lirico, Cagliari]].<ref>[http://www.ansa.it/sardegna/notizie/2017/11/21/cagliari-prima-europea-de-la-ciociara_e18a40da-f97e-4e35-aee9-e644c4aff8d5.html \"Cagliari, prima europea de La Ciociara Compositore Tutino, ''una storia di cui si parla poco''\" at ansa.it/sardegna] Accessed 13 December 2017</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|La Ciociara (film)}}\n*{{IMDb title|0054749|Two Women}}\n*{{Rotten Tomatoes|two_women}}\n*[http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/99299%7C0/Two-Women.html ''Two Women''] at [[TCMDB]]\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=EE05E7DF173FE177BC4153DFB366838A679EDE Review of film] at [[New York Times]]\n*[http://www.lefilmguide.com/review/la-ciociara-1960.html Film page] at Le Film Guide\n{{Vittorio De Sica}}\n