age=French}}</ref>\n| [[Grand Prix (Belgian Syndicate of Cinema Critics)|Grand Prix]]\n!\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | January 7, 2008\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[13th Critics' Choice Awards|Broadcast Film Critics Association]]<ref name=\"BFCAA\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7176289.stm |title=Coens land Critics' Choice Awards |accessdate=2008-01-08 |date=2008-01-08 |work=BBC News}}</ref>\n| [[Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n!\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n| Daniel Day-Lewis\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Composer|Best Composer]]\n| Jonny Greenwood\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| January 26, 2008\n| [[Directors Guild of America Awards 2007|Directors Guild of America]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Directors Guild announces nominations |work=Rope of Silicon |date=2007-12-20 |url=http://www.ropeofsilicon.com/article/directors_guild_announces_their_2008_nominees |accessdate=2007-12-31}}</ref>\n| [[Directors Guild of America Award for Outstanding Directing \u2013 Feature Film|Outstanding Directing \u2013 Feature Film]]\n| Paul Thomas Anderson\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | January 13, 2008\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[65th Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe Awards]]<ref name=\"GGAwards\">\"2007 Golden Globe Nominations and Winners\". Hollywood Foreign Press Association. 2012-05-24</ref>\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Drama|Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Drama]]\n| Daniel Day-Lewis\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Drama]]\n!\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n|-\n| rowspan=\"8\" | January 4, 2009\n| rowspan=\"8\" | [[International Online Film Critics' Poll]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/site/internationalonlinefilmcritics/editions/1st-edition|title=1st Edition - International Online Film Critics' Poll|publisher=}}</ref>\n| Best Film \u2013 Motion Picture\n!\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Top Ten Films\n!\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Best Director\n| Paul Thomas Anderson\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Actor\n| Daniel Day-Lewis\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Best Ensemble Cast\n| Paul Thomas Anderson\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Screenplay \u2013 Adapted\n| Paul Thomas Anderson\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Production Design\n| Jack Fisk, Jim Erickson\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Cinematography\n| Robert Elswit\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | January 9, 2011\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[List of film awards|International Online Film Critics' Poll]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/site/internationalonlinefilmcritics/editions/2nd-edition|title=2nd Edition - International Online Film Critics' Poll|publisher=}}</ref>\n| Top Ten Films \u2013 Decade\n!\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Best Actor \u2013 Decade\n| Daniel Day-Lewis\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\" | December 9, 2007\n| rowspan=\"7\" | [[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Awards 2007|Los Angeles Film Critics Association]]<ref>{{cite web |last=Giles |first=Jeff |title=There Will Be Blood, No Country For Old Men Top Critics' Awards: New York, LA, Boston and D.C. scribes honor the best of 2007 |work=Rotten Tomatoes |publisher=Flixter |date=2007-12-10 |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/there_will_be_blood/news/1696306 |accessdate=2007-12-22}}</ref>\n| [[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n!\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n| Paul Thomas Anderson\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n| Daniel Day-Lewis\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]]\n| Paul Thomas Anderson\n| {{draw|Runner-up}}\n|-\n| [[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]]\n| Robert Elswit\n| {{draw|Runner-up}}\n|-\n| Best Production Design\n| Jack Fisk\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Music|Best Music]]\n| Jonny Greenwood\n| {{draw|Runner-up}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" | January 5, 2008\n| rowspan=\"5\" | [[National Society of Film Critics Awards 2007|National Society of Film Critics]]<ref>{{cite web |last=Hernandez |first=Eugene |title='There Will Be Blood' Leads National Society of Film Critics Awards: Best Picture, Director, Actor, Cinematography |work=indieWIRE |date=2008-01-05 |url=http://www.indiewire.com/biz/2008/01/awards_watch_th_1.html |accessdate=2008-01-05 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080107042328/http://www.indiewire.com/biz/2008/01/awards_watch_th_1.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate=2008-01-07}}</ref>\n| [[National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n!\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n| Paul Thomas Anderson\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n| Daniel Day-Lewis\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]]\n| Paul Thomas Anderson\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]]\n| Robert Elswit\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| January 27, 2008\n| [[14th Screen Actors Guild Awards|Screen Actors Guild Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sagawards.org/PR_080127 |title=Final 14th Annual SAG Awards Recipient Press Release |accessdate=2008-01-27 |date=2008-01-27 |work=Screen Actors Guild |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509081608/http://www.sagawards.org/PR_080127 |archivedate=May 9, 2008 }}</ref>\n| [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Leading Role|Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Leading Role]]\n| Daniel Day-Lewis\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| 2007\n| [[Writers Guild of America Awards 2007|Writers Guild of America Awards]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.emanuellevy.com/oscar/oscar-2007-writers-guild-calls-off-its-awards-show-8 |title=Oscar 2007: Writers Guild Calls Off Its Awards Show |accessdate=2011-01-03 |work=Emanuel Levy}}</ref>\n| [[Writers Guild of America Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]]\n| Paul Thomas Anderson {{small|(Screenplay)}}; [[Upton Sinclair]] {{small|(Author)}}\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| February 2, 2008\n| [[Producers Guild of America Awards 2007|Producers Guild of America Awards]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.enotes.com/topic/Producers_Guild_of_America_Award_for_Best_Theatrical_Motion_Picture |title=Producers Guild of America Award for Best Theatrical Motion Pictur e|accessdate=2011-01-03 |work=eNotes}}</ref>\n| [[Producers Guild of America Award for Best Theatrical Motion Picture|Best Theatrical Motion Picture]]\n!\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| January 26, 2008\n| [[American Society of Cinematographers Awards 2007|American Society of Cinematographers Awards]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theasc.com/news/awards/awards_history.php |title=The ASC Awards for Outstanding Achievement in Cinematography |accessdate=2011-01-03 |work=American Society of Cinematographers |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101229223539/http://www.theasc.com/news/awards/awards_history.php |archivedate=2010-12-29 }}</ref>\n| [[American Society of Cinematographers Award for Outstanding Achievement in Cinematography in Theatrical Releases|Outstanding Achievement in Cinematography in Theatrical Releases]]\n| Robert Elswit\n| {{Won}}\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of films featuring the deaf and hard of hearing]]\n{{Portal bar|Film}}\n\n== References ==\n<!-- To cite a web resource, see template:cite web -->\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote|There Will Be Blood}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.miramax.com/movie/there-will-be-blood}}\n* {{IMDb title|0469494|There Will Be Blood}}\n* {{AllRovi movie|346474|There Will Be Blood}}\n* {{Mojo title|therewillbeblood|There Will Be Blood}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|there_will_be_blood}}\n* {{Metacritic film|there-will-be-blood|There Will Be Blood}}\n\n{{s-start}} {{s-ach|aw}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Film|LAFCA Award for Best Film]]\n| years = 2007\n| before= ''[[Letters from Iwo Jima]]''\n| after = ''[[WALL-E]]''\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Film|NSFC Award for Best Film]]\n| years = 2007\n| before= ''[[Pan's Labyrinth]]''\n| after = ''[[Waltz with Bashir]]''\n}}\n{{end}}\n{{Paul Thomas Anderson}}\n{{Upton Sinclair}}\n{{Los Angeles Film Critics Association Award for Best Film}}\n{{National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Film}}\n\n[[Category:2007 films]]\n[[Category:American Sign Language films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:2000s drama films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American epic films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (films)]]\n[[Category:Films about cults]]\n[[Category:Films about deaf people]]\n[[Category:Films based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Paul Thomas Anderson]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Actor Academy Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Drama Actor Golden Globe winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Scott Rudin]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1898]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1902]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1911]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1927]]\n[[Category:Films set in California]]\n[[Category:Films set in New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Texas]]\n[[Category:Films whose cinematographer won the Best Cinematography Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Paul Thomas Anderson]]\n[[Category:Mining in film]]\n[[Category:Films about narcissism]]\n[[Category:Petroleum in California]]\n[[Category:Works about petroleum]]\n[[Category:Films about curses]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Jonny Greenwood]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by Upton Sinclair]]\n[[Category:Silver Bear for outstanding artistic contribution]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2007 film by Paul Thomas Anderson}}{{About|the film|the Flash episode|There Will Be Blood (The Flash)|the Kim Petras song|Turn Off the Light (album)|the Sum 41 song|13 Voices}}{{redirect|TWBB|the Chinese company|Tianwei Baobian Electric}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = There Will Be Blood\n| image          = There Will Be Blood Poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster featuring Daniel Day-Lewis\n| director       = [[Paul Thomas Anderson]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[JoAnne Sellar]]\n* Paul Thomas Anderson\n* [[Daniel Lupi]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = Paul Thomas Anderson\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Oil!]]''|[[Upton Sinclair]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Daniel Day-Lewis]]\n* [[Paul Dano]]\n* [[Kevin J. O'Connor (actor)|Kevin J. O'Connor]]\n* [[Ciar\u00e1n Hinds]]\n* [[Dillon Freasier]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Jonny Greenwood]]\n| cinematography = [[Robert Elswit]]\n| editing        = [[Dylan Tichenor]]\n| studio         = [[Paul Thomas Anderson|Ghoulardi Film Company]]\n| distributor    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Paramount Vantage]]\n* [[Miramax|Miramax Films]]\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2007|09|27|[[Fantastic Fest]]|2007|12|26|United States}}\n| runtime        = 158 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $25 million<ref name=\"BoxOfficeMojo\">{{cite web |title=There Will Be Blood (2007) |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=therewillbeblood.htm |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=April 28, 2008}}</ref>\n| gross          = $76.2 million<ref name=\"BoxOfficeMojo\" />\n}}\n\n'''''There Will Be Blood''''' is a 2007 American [[epic film|epic]] [[period film|period]] [[drama film]] written and directed by [[Paul Thomas Anderson]], loosely based on the novel ''[[Oil!]]'' by [[Upton Sinclair]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://explore.bfi.org.uk/sightandsoundpolls/2012/film/4ce2b8c6518bb|title=There Will Be Blood (2007)|publisher=[[The British Film Institute]]}}</ref> It stars [[Daniel Day-Lewis]] as a silver miner-turned-oilman on a ruthless quest for wealth during [[History of oil in California through 1930|Southern California's oil boom]] of the late 19th and early 20th centuries. [[Paul Dano]], [[Kevin J. O'Connor (actor)|Kevin J. O'Connor]], [[Ciar\u00e1n Hinds]], and [[Dillon Freasier]]  also feature in the film.\n\nThe film was produced by [[Paul Thomas Anderson|Ghoulardi Film Company]] and distributed by [[Paramount Vantage]] and [[Miramax|Miramax Films]]. It premiered at the [[Berlin International Film Festival]], where it won the [[Silver Bear for Best Director|Silver Bear Award for Best Director]] and a Special Artistic Contribution Award for [[Jonny Greenwood]]'s score. The film grossed $76.2 million worldwide against its $25 million budget.\n\n''There Will Be Blood'' received significant critical praise for its cinematography, direction, screenplay, and particularly the performance of Day-Lewis, who won [[Academy Award|Oscar]], [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA]], [[Golden Globe]], [[Screen Actors Guild]], [[NYFCC Award|NYFCC]] and [[IFTA Award|IFTA]] Best Actor awards for the role. It appears on several lists of the greatest films of the 21st century,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/06/09/movies/the-25-best-films-of-the-21st-century.html|title=The 25 Best Films of the 21st Century So Far.|date=2017-06-09|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-06-12|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20160819-the-21st-centurys-100-greatest-films|title=The 21st Century\u2019s 100 greatest films|last=2016|publisher=BBC|first=23 August|language=en|access-date=2018-09-27}}</ref> and appeared on many critics' \"top ten\" lists for the year, including the [[American Film Institute Awards 2007|American Film Institute]],<ref>[http://www.afi.com/tvevents/afiawards07/default.aspx \"AFI Awards 2007\"]. ''American Film Institute''. Retrieved November 18, 2012.</ref> the [[National Society of Film Critics]], the [[National Board of Review: Top Ten Films#2000s|National Board of Review]], and the [[Los Angeles Film Critics Association]]. At the [[80th Academy Awards]], the film was nominated for eight [[Academy Awards|Oscars]] (tying with another Paramount Vantage/Miramax co-production [[No Country for Old Men (film)|''No Country for Old Men'']]).  The nominations included the [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] and [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]] for Anderson.  The film won two Oscars: [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] for Day-Lewis and the [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]] for [[Robert Elswit]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/film-critics-pick-the-best-movies-of-the-decade|title=Critics Pick the Best Movies of the Decade&nbsp;\u2014 Metacritic|work=Metacritic}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\nIn 1898, Daniel Plainview is a silver prospector mining a potentially precious [[vein (geology)|ore vein]] from a pit mine hole in [[New Mexico]]. In the process of dynamiting the [[lode]], he falls and breaks his leg. He saves a silver sample, climbs out of the mine and drags himself to an assay office, where he receives a silver and gold certificate [[land claim|claim]]. In 1902, [[history of oil in California through 1930|he discovers oil near Los Angeles]] and establishes a drilling company. Following the death of a worker in an accident, Daniel adopts the man's orphaned son. The boy, H. W., becomes his nominal business partner, allowing Daniel to present himself to potential investors as a family man.\n\nIn 1911, Daniel is approached by Paul Sunday, a young man who tells him of an oil deposit under his family's property in Little Boston, California. Daniel attempts to purchase the farm from the Sundays at a bargain price, but he is blocked by Eli, Paul's twin brother and a local evangelical preacher. In exchange for the rights to the property, Eli demands $10,000 \"for his church.\" An agreement is made and Daniel acquires all the available land in and around the Sunday property, save for one holdout: William Bandy.\n\nOil drilling commences, but soon a series of misfortunes occur: an accident kills one worker and a [[blowout (well drilling)|gas blowout]] deafens H. W. Eli blames the disasters on the well not being properly blessed. When Eli publicly demands the money still owed to him, Daniel beats and humiliates him. At the dinner table that night, Eli attacks and berates his father for trusting Daniel.\n\nA man arrives at Daniel's doorstep claiming to be his half-brother, Henry. Daniel hires Henry and the two grow close. A jealous H. W. sets fire to their house, intending to kill Henry. A furious Daniel sends H. W. away to a school for the deaf in [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]]. A representative from [[Standard Oil]] offers to buy out Daniel's local interests, but after a perceived slight, Daniel refuses and strikes a deal with [[Union Oil]] to build a pipeline to the California coast. However, Bandy's ranch remains an impediment.\n\nReminiscing about his childhood, Daniel becomes suspicious to the truth of Henry's story and confronts him one night at gunpoint. \"Henry\" confesses that he was a friend of the real Henry, who died of [[tuberculosis]], and that he impersonated Henry in hopes of gaining employment with Daniel. In a fit of rage, Daniel murders the impostor and buries his body.\n\nThe next morning, Daniel is awakened by Bandy, who knows of Daniel's crime and wants Daniel to publicly repent in Eli's church in exchange for the pipeline construction rights on his land. As part of his [[baptism]], Eli humiliates Daniel and coerces him into confessing that he abandoned his son. Some time later, as the pipeline is under construction, H. W. is reunited with Daniel and Eli leaves Little Boston for missionary work.\n\nIn 1927, H. W. marries Mary Sunday, the younger sister of Paul and Eli. He visits Daniel, who is now an extremely wealthy but [[alcoholism|alcoholic]] recluse in a large mansion. Through a [[language interpretation|sign language interpreter]], H. W. asks his father to dissolve their partnership so that he can establish his own independent drilling company in [[Mexico]]. Daniel reacts brutally, mocking H. W.'s deafness before revealing his true origins as an orphan \"bastard from a basket.\" H. W. tells Daniel he is glad that they are not related and storms out.\n\nEli visits Daniel, who is drunk in his private [[bowling alley]]. Eli, now a radio preacher, offers to sell Daniel the property rights to the Bandy ranch, as William Bandy has recently died. Daniel agrees on the condition that Eli denounce his faith and his own credibility. Eli reluctantly acquiesces, only for Daniel to then reveal that the property is now worthless because he has already drained its oil by [[slant drilling]] from neighboring wells. Shaken, Eli confesses to being in dire financial straits and to having strayed morally. Daniel taunts Eli in revenge for his own previous humiliation before chasing him around the bowling alley and eventually beats him to death with a bowling pin. Exhausted, Daniel collapses on the floor next to Eli's body and announces that he is \"finished.\"\n\n== Cast ==\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Daniel Day-Lewis]] as Daniel Plainview\n* [[Paul Dano]] as Paul Sunday and Eli Sunday\n* [[Kevin J. O'Connor (actor)|Kevin J. O'Connor]] as Henry\n* [[Ciar\u00e1n Hinds]] as Fletcher Hamilton\n* [[Dillon Freasier]] as H. W. Plainview\n* [[Russell Harvard]] as adult H. W. Plainview\n* Sydney McCallister as young Mary Sunday\n* Colleen Foy as adult Mary Sunday\n* David Willis as Abel Sunday\n* Hans Howes as William Bandy\n* [[Paul F. Tompkins]] as Prescott\n* [[Jim Downey (comedian)|Jim Downey]] as Al Rose\n* [[David Warshofsky]] as H. M. Tilford\n* [[Barry Del Sherman]] as H. B. Ailman\n}}\n\n== Themes and analysis ==\nMany have seen the film as a commentary on the nature of capitalism and greed, and its inherent national presence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://freepress.org/article/there-will-be-blood-madness-american-capitalismbut-no-method|title=There Will Be Blood: The madness of American capitalism...but no method|publisher=|accessdate=11 January 2017}}</ref> Daniel Plainview's \"I have a competition in me\" speech has been looked at as key when analyzing the film from this angle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://warandnoise.com/therewillbeblood/|title=A Critical Analysis of There Will Be Blood: Intensional Godhood - Noisewar Internetlainen|publisher=|accessdate=11 January 2017}}</ref> David Denby of the ''New Yorker'' described the film as being about \"...the driving force of capitalism as it both creates and destroys the future...\" and goes on to say that \"this movie is about the vanishing American frontier. The thrown-together buildings look scraggly and unkempt, the homesteaders are modest, stubborn, and reticent, but, in their undreamed-of future, Wal-Mart is on the way.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2007/12/17/hard-life-2-2|title=Hard Life|publisher=|accessdate=11 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nOthers have noted themes of faith, religion, and family.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unomaha.edu/jrf/vol12no2/Reviews/ThereWillBBlood.htm|title=University of Nebraska Omaha|accessdate=11 January 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150910033735/http://www.unomaha.edu/jrf/vol12no2/Reviews/ThereWillBBlood.htm|archivedate=10 September 2015}}</ref> Many feel that the contrast between Daniel and Eli highlights the disparity between faith and avarice. James Christopher of ''The Times'' viewed the film as  \"...a biblical parable about America's failure to square religion and greed.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nonesuch.com/journal/times-uk-evening-standard-give-there-will-be-blood-five-stars|title=Nonesuch Records Times (UK), Evening Standard Give \"There Will Be Blood\" Five Stars|publisher=|accessdate=11 January 2017}}</ref> Others have noted how the absence of family and resulting isolation in Daniel's life plays a large role in his eventual descent into madness.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/55468331|title=There will be blood Analysis|publisher=|accessdate=11 January 2017}}</ref> By the film's end, having felt betrayed by both Henry (his false brother) and H.W. (his non-biological son), he reacts by murdering Eli. Critics and essayists also argue that these killings and rejections are Daniel's way of eliminating any possible source of competition in the oil industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0469494/faq#.2.1.12|title=There Will Be Blood|date=25 January 2008|publisher=|accessdate=11 January 2017|via=IMDb}}</ref>\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== Development ===\n[[File:Paul Thomas Anderson & Daniel Day-Lewis-2.jpg|thumb|right|[[Paul Thomas Anderson]] and [[Daniel Day-Lewis]] in New York, December 2007.]]\nAfter [[Eric Schlosser]] finished writing ''[[Fast Food Nation]]'', reporters kept asking him about Upton Sinclair. Although he had read Sinclair's ''[[The Jungle]]'', he did not know about his other works or anything about Sinclair himself. He decided to read most of Sinclair's works, and eventually read the novel ''[[Oil!]]'', which he loved. Schlosser, who found the book to be exciting and thought it would make a great film, sought out the Sinclair estate and purchased the film rights. He thought that he would try to find a director who was as passionate about the book as he was, but director Paul Thomas Anderson approached him first.<ref name=\"ES-TNYT-2008\">{{cite news |author=Schlosser, Eric  |date=February 22, 2008 |title='Oil!' and the History of Southern California |newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nAnderson had been working on a screenplay about two fighting families. He struggled with the script and soon realized it was not working.<ref name=\"Stern\">{{cite news |author=Stern, Marlow |title='There Will Be Blood' Press Conference |work=Manhattan Movie Magazine |date=December 10, 2007 |url= |accessdate=}}</ref> Homesick, he purchased a copy of ''Oil!'' in [[London, England|London]], drawn to its cover illustration of a California oilfield.<ref name=\"Goodwin\">{{cite news |author=Goodwin, Christopher |title=Daniel Day-Lewis Gives Blood, Sweat and Tears |newspaper=The Sunday Times |date=November 25, 2007 |url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article2922563.ece |accessdate=December 21, 2009 |location=London}}</ref> As he read, Anderson became more fascinated with the novel. After contacting Schlosser, he adapted the first 150 pages to a screenplay. He began to get a real sense of where his script was going after making many trips to museums dedicated to early oilmen in [[Bakersfield, California|Bakersfield]].<ref name=\"Hirschberg\">{{cite news |author=Hirschberg, Lynn |title=The New Frontier's Man |newspaper=The New York Times Magazine |date=December 11, 2007 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/11/magazine/11daylewis-t2.html?_r=2&adxnnl=1&oref=slogin&adxnnlx=1197697066-ZGxe5I9RiTtwkgTydXd2Dg&oref=slogin |accessdate=December 31, 2007}}</ref> Anderson changed the title from ''Oil!'' to ''There Will Be Blood'' because he felt \"there's not enough of the book to feel like it's a proper adaptation\".<ref name=\"Stern\" />\n\nHe said of writing the screenplay:\n{{quote|I can remember the way that my desk looked, with so many different scraps of paper and books about the oil industry in the early 20th century, mixed in with pieces of other scripts that I'd written. Everything was coming from so many different sources. But the book was a great stepping-stone. It was so cohesive, the way Upton Sinclair wrote about that period, and his experiences around the oil fields and these independent oilmen. That said, the book is so long that it's only the first couple hundred pages that we ended up using, because there is a certain point where he strays really far from what the original story is. We were really unfaithful to the book. That's not to say I didn't really like the book; I loved it. But there were so many other things floating around. And at a certain point, I became aware of the stuff he was basing it on. What he was writing about was the life of [oil barons] [[Edward L. Doheny|Edward Doheny]] and [[Harry Ford Sinclair|Harry Sinclair]]. So it was like having a really good collaborator, the book.<ref name=\"Modell\">{{cite web |last=Modell |first=Josh |title=Paul Thomas Anderson |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/paul-thomas-anderson,2120 |work=The A.V. Club |accessdate=September 2, 2012 |date=January 2, 2008}}</ref>}}\n\nAnderson, who had previously said that he would like to work with Daniel Day-Lewis,<ref name=\"Patterson\">{{cite news |author=Patterson, John |title='Magnolia' Maniac |newspaper=The Guardian |date=March 10, 2000 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2000/mar/10/culture.features |accessdate=April 12, 2010 |location=London}}</ref> wrote the screenplay with Day-Lewis in mind and approached the actor when the script was nearly complete. Anderson had heard that Day-Lewis liked his earlier film ''[[Punch-Drunk Love]]'', which gave him the confidence to hand Day-Lewis a copy of the incomplete script.<ref name=\"LATimesLewis\">{{cite news |title=Prospectors Anderson and Day-Lewis Strike Black Gold |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=December 19, 2007 }}</ref> According to Day-Lewis, being asked to do the film was enough to convince him.<ref name=\"Freydkin\">{{cite news |author=Freydkin, Donna |title=Daniel Day-Lewis has recognition in his 'Blood' |newspaper=USA Today |date=December 10, 2007 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/people/2007-12-10-blood-premiere_N.htm |accessdate=December 21, 2007}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[The New York Observer]]'', he elaborated that what drew him to the project was \"the understanding that [Anderson] had already entered into that world, [he] wasn't observing it {{ndash}} [he'd] entered into it {{ndash}} and indeed [he'd] populated it with characters who [he] felt had lives of their own\".<ref name=\"Vilkomerson\">{{cite news |author=Vilkomerson, Sarah |title=P.S. I Love You Daniel Day-Lewis |newspaper=New York Observer |date=December 18, 2007 |url=http://www.nyobserver.com/2007/sara-vilkomerson-s-guide-week-s-movies-p-s-i-love-you-daniel-day-lewis |accessdate=December 31, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071225010901/http://www.nyobserver.com/2007/sara-vilkomerson-s-guide-week-s-movies-p-s-i-love-you-daniel-day-lewis |archivedate=December 25, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nAnderson said that the line in the final scene, \"I drink your [[milkshake]]!\", was paraphrased from a quote by former Secretary of the Interior and [[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]] from [[New Mexico]], [[Albert Fall]], speaking before a Congressional investigation into the 1920s oil-related [[Teapot Dome scandal]]. Anderson said he was fascinated \"to see that word [milkshake] among all this official testimony and terminology\" to explain the complicated process of oil drainage.<ref>{{cite news |author=Foundas, Scott |date=January 16, 2008 |url=http://www.laweekly.com/2008-01-17/film-tv/blood-sweat-and-tears |title=Paul Thomas Anderson: Blood, Sweat and Tears |newspaper=LA Weekly |accessdate=May 25, 2010}}</ref> In 2013, an independent attempt to locate the statement in Fall's testimony proved unsuccessful\u2014an article published in the Case Western Reserve Law Review suggested that the actual source of the paraphrased quote may instead have been remarks in 2003 by Sen. [[Pete Domenici]] of New Mexico during a debate over drilling in the [[Arctic National Wildlife Refuge]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Peter M. Gerhart & Robert D. Cheren |url=http://law.case.edu/journals/LawReview/Documents/63CaseWResLRev4.4.Article.GerhartCheren.pdf |title=Recognizing the Shared Ownership of Subsurface Resource Pools |publisher=63 Case W. Res. L. Rev. 1041, 1047 n.9 (2013) |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104184051/http://law.case.edu/journals/LawReview/Documents/63CaseWResLRev4.4.Article.GerhartCheren.pdf |archivedate=2013-11-04 }}</ref> In those remarks, Domenici stated:<ref>149 Cong. Rec. 6729 (2003).</ref>\n\n{{Quote|The oil is underground, and it is going to be drilled and come up. Here is a giant reservoir underground. Just like a curved straw, you put it underground and maneuver it, and the 'milk shake' is way over there, and your little child wants the milk shake, and they sit over here in their bedroom where they are feeling ill, and they just gobble it up from way down in the kitchen, where you don't even have to move the Mix Master that made the ice cream for them. You don't have to take it up to the bedroom. This describes the actual drilling that is taking place.}}\n\nAccording to Joanne Sellar, one of the film's producers, it was a hard film to finance because \"the studios didn't think it had the scope of a major picture\".<ref name=\"Goodwin\" /> It took two years to acquire financing for the film.<ref name=\"Hirschberg\" /> For the role of Plainview's \"son\", Anderson looked at people in [[Los Angeles]] and [[New York City]], but he realized that they needed someone from [[Texas]] who knew how to shoot [[shotgun]]s and \"live in that world\".<ref name=\"Stern\" /> The filmmakers asked around at a school and the principal recommended [[Dillon Freasier]]. They did not have him read any scenes and instead talked to him, realizing that he was the perfect person for the role.<ref name=\"Stern\" />\n\nTo build his character, Day-Lewis started with the voice. Anderson sent him recordings from the late 19th century to 1927 and a copy of the 1948 film ''[[The Treasure of the Sierra Madre (film)|The Treasure of the Sierra Madre]]'', including documentaries on its director, [[John Huston]], an important influence on Anderson's film.<ref name=\"Goodwin\" /> According to Anderson, he was inspired by the fact that ''Sierra Madre'' is \"about greed and ambition and paranoia and looking at the worst parts of yourself\".<ref name=\"Hirschberg\" /> While writing the script, he would put the film on before he went to bed at night. To research for the role, Day-Lewis read letters from laborers and studied photographs from the time period. He also read up on oil tycoon [[Edward Doheny]], upon whom Sinclair's book is loosely based.<ref name=\"Lewis\">{{cite news |author=Lewis, Judith |title=Daniel Day-Lewis: The Way He Lives Now |newspaper=L.A. Weekly |date=December 19, 2007 |url=http://www.laweekly.com/film+tv/film/daniel-day-lewis-the-way-he-lives-now/17906 |accessdate=December 31, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071223021614/http://www.laweekly.com/film+tv/film/daniel-day-lewis-the-way-he-lives-now/17906 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate=December 23, 2007}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\n[[Principal photography]] began in June 2006 on a ranch in [[Marfa, Texas]],<ref name=\"Hirschberg\" /> and took three months.<ref name=\"Goodwin\" /> Other location shooting took place in Los Angeles. Anderson tried to shoot the script in sequence with most of the sets on the ranch.<ref name=\"Hirschberg\" /> Two weeks in, Anderson replaced the actor playing Eli Sunday with [[Paul Dano]], who had originally only been cast in the much smaller role of Paul Sunday, the brother who tipped off Plainview about the oil on the Sunday ranch. A profile of Day-Lewis in ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'' suggested that the original actor, [[Kel O'Neill]], had been intimidated by Day-Lewis's intensity and habit of staying in character on and off the set.<ref name=\"Hirschberg\" /><ref name=\"Lewis\" /> Both Anderson and Day-Lewis deny this claim,<ref name=\"Hirschberg\" /><ref name=\"Lewis\" /> and Day-Lewis stated, \"I absolutely don't believe that it was because he was intimidated by me. I happen to believe that\u2014and I hope I'm right.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Longsdorf |first=Amy |title=In 'Blood,' Day-Lewis unearths an oil tycoon's complexities |newspaper=The Morning Call |date=January 3, 2008 |url=http://www.mcall.com/entertainment/movies/all-go_movies.6208480jan03,0,5814474.story |accessdate=December 31, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080115004440/http://www.mcall.com/entertainment/movies/all-go_movies.6208480jan03,0,5814474.story |archivedate=January 15, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nAnderson first saw Dano in ''[[The Ballad of Jack and Rose]]'' and thought that he would be perfect to play Paul Sunday, a role he originally envisioned to be a 12- or 13-year-old boy. Dano only had four days to prepare for the much larger role of Eli Sunday,<ref name=\"National Public Radio Audio Interview, January 8, 2008\">{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=17926946 |title=National Public Radio Audio Interview |publisher=NPR.org |accessdate=November 18, 2012}}</ref> but he researched the time period that the film is set in as well as [[Evangelism|evangelical]] preachers.<ref name=\"Stern\" /> The previous two weeks of scenes with Sunday and Plainview had to be re-shot with Dano instead of O'Neill.<ref name=\"Hirschberg\" /> The interior mansion scenes were filmed at the [[Greystone Mansion]] in [[Beverly Hills, California|Beverly Hills]], the former real-life home of Edward Doheny Jr., a gift from his father, [[Edward Doheny]]. Scenes filmed at Greystone involved the careful renovation of the basement's two-lane bowling alley.<ref name=\"LATimesHobart\">{{cite news |last=Hobart |first=Christy |title=At Greystone, there will be 'Blood' -- and bowling |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |pages=F1, F4 |date=December 27, 2007 |url=http://www.latimes.com/features/home/la-hm-blood27dec27,1,6977925.story?ctrack=2&cset=true |accessdate=December 31, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080119060955/http://www.latimes.com/features/home/la-hm-blood27dec27,1,6977925.story?ctrack=2&cset=true <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate=January 19, 2008}}</ref> Anderson said it was \"a particular situation, because it was so narrow that there could only be a very limited number of people at any given time, maybe five or six behind the camera and then the two boys.\"<ref name=\"Modell\" />\n\nAnderson dedicated the film to [[Robert Altman]], who died while Anderson was editing it.<ref name=\"Stern\" />\n\n''There Will Be Blood'' was shot using [[Panavision]] XL [[35mm movie film|35 mm]] cameras outfitted primarily with Panavision C series and high-speed [[anamorphic]] lenses.<ref name=\"DigContentProducer\">{{cite web |last=Goldman |first=Michael |title=Old-Fashioned Filmmaking |date=November 1, 2007 |url=http://digitalcontentproducer.com/mil/features/video_oldfashioned_filmmaking/index2.html |accessdate=February 24, 2008}}</ref>\n\nDay-Lewis broke a rib in a fall during filming.<ref>{{cite web |title=A Pinewood Dialogue with Daniel Day-Lewis and Paul Thomas Anderson (Transcript) |url=http://www.movingimagesource.us/files/dialogues/2/96175_programs_transcript_html_296.htm |date=December 11, 2007 |accessdate=February 21, 2011 |work=Museum of the Moving Image}}</ref>\n\n=== Music ===\n{{Further|There Will Be Blood (album)}}\nAnderson had been a fan of [[Radiohead]]'s music and was impressed with [[Jonny Greenwood]]'s scoring of the film ''[[Bodysong]]''. While writing the script for ''There Will Be Blood'', Anderson heard Greenwood's orchestral piece \"Popcorn Superhet Receiver\", which prompted him to ask Greenwood to work with him. After initially agreeing to score the film, Greenwood had doubts and thought about backing out, but Anderson's reassurance and enthusiasm for the film convinced him to stick with it.<ref name=\"Willman\">{{cite news |last=Willman |first=Chris |title=There Will Be Music |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=December 2007 |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20155516_20155530_20158721,00.html |accessdate=December 21, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Ponto\">{{cite news |last=Ponto |first=Arya |title=Jonny Greenwood scoring PTA's new film |work=Just Press Play |date=September 7, 2007 |url=http://www.justpressplay.net/movies/there-will-be-blood/news/radioheads-jonny-greenwood-scoring-ptas-new-film.html |accessdate=December 21, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926235832/http://www.justpressplay.net/movies/there-will-be-blood/news/radioheads-jonny-greenwood-scoring-ptas-new-film.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate=September 26, 2007}}</ref> Anderson gave Greenwood a copy of the film and three weeks later he came back with two hours of music recorded at [[Abbey Road Studios]] in London.<ref name=\"Stern\" /> Concerning his approach to composing the soundtrack, Greenwood said to ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'':\n\n{{quote|I think it was about not necessarily just making period music, which very traditionally you would do. But because they were traditional orchestral sounds, I suppose that's what we hoped was a little unsettling, even though you know all the sounds you're hearing are coming from very old technology. You can just do things with the classical orchestra that do unsettle you, that are sort of slightly wrong, that have some kind of undercurrent that's slightly sinister.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/extendedplay/2007/11/after-a-screeni.html |last=Martens |first=Todd |title=Radiohead's Greenwood goes sinister for 'There Will Be Blood' |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=May 25, 2010}}</ref>}}\n\nSome of [[Krzysztof Penderecki]]'s [[Work of art|oeuvre]] was the inspiration for [[Jonny Greenwood]] of [[Radiohead]] to release an album, which thereafter appeared in the score of this film.<ref name=\"Levenson\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/29/world/krzysztof-penderecki-composer-death-trnd/index.html |title=Krzysztof Penderecki, composer of works in 'The Exorcist' and 'The Shining,' dies at 86 |first1=Eric |last1=Levenson |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2008, Greenwood's score was nominated for a Grammy in the category of \"Best Score Soundtrack Album for Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media\" for the [[51st Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content.grammy.com/grammy_awards/51st_show/list.aspx#22 |title=51st Grammy Awards Nomination List |year=2008 |work=Grammy.com |accessdate=January 2, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205000233/http://content.grammy.com/grammy_awards/51st_show/list.aspx#22 |archivedate=December 5, 2008 }}</ref> It features classical music, such as the third movement (\"Vivace Non Troppo\") of [[Johannes Brahms]]'s [[Violin Concerto (Brahms)|Violin Concerto in D Major]] in the gas blowout scene (when H.W. is injured) and in the ending titles, and [[Arvo P\u00e4rt]]'s \"[[Fratres]]\" for cello and piano.<ref>{{Citation|title=There Will Be Blood (2007) - IMDb|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0469494/soundtrack|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nGreenwood's score was awarded the [[Silver Bear]] for outstanding artistic contribution (music) at the [[58th Berlin International Film Festival]] in 2008.<ref>[https://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/2008/03_preistr_ger_2008/03_Preistraeger_2008.html Berlinale. Archiv. Prize winners 2008]. Retrieved 27 January 2019.</ref>\n\n== Release ==\n\n=== Critical reception ===\nReview aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives a score of 91% based on reviews from 232 critics, with an average rating of 8.43/10. The consensus reads, \"Widely touted as a masterpiece, this sparse and sprawling epic about the underhanded \"heroes\" of capitalism boasts incredible performances by leads Daniel Day-Lewis and Paul Dano, and is director Paul Thomas Anderson's best work to date.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/there_will_be_blood |title=There Will Be Blood |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Rotten Tomatoes |publisher= Flixster}}</ref>\nOn [[Metacritic]], the film has an average score of 93/100, based on 42 reviews indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/therewillbeblood |title=There Will Be Blood |accessdate=March 5, 2008 |work=Metacritic |publisher=CBS Interactive}}</ref>\n\n[[Andrew Sarris]] called the film \"an impressive achievement in its confident expertness in rendering the simulated realities of a bygone time and place, largely with an inspired use of regional amateur actors and extras with all the right moves and sounds.\"<ref name=\"Sarris\">{{cite news |last=Sarris |first=Andrew |title=Oil, Oil Everywhere! |work=New York Observer |date=December 17, 2007 |url= |accessdate=}}</ref> In ''[[Premiere (magazine)|Premiere]]'', [[Glenn Kenny]] praised Day-Lewis's performance: \"Once his Plainview takes wing, the relentless focus of the performance makes the character unique.\"<ref name=\"Kenny\">{{cite news |last=Kenny |first=Glenn |title='There Will Be Blood' |work=Premiere.com |date=December 13, 2007 |url=http://www.premiere.com/moviereviews/4316/there-will-be-blood.html |accessdate=December 31, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071229223706/http://www.premiere.com/moviereviews/4316/there-will-be-blood.html |archivedate=December 29, 2007 }}</ref>\n[[Manohla Dargis]] wrote, in her review for ''[[The New York Times]]'', \"the film is above all a consummate work of art, one that transcends the historically fraught context of its making, and its pleasures are unapologetically aesthetic.\"<ref name=\"Dargis\">{{cite news |last=Dargis |first=Manohla |title=An American Primitive, Forged in a Crucible of Blood and Oil |work=The New York Times |date=December 26, 2007 |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/2007/12/26/movies/26bloo.html?ref=movies |accessdate=December 31, 2007}}</ref>\n''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'' also praised Day-Lewis' performance: \"what's most fun, albeit in a frightening way, is watching this greedmeister become more and more unhinged as he locks horns with Eli Sunday \u2026 both Anderson and Day-Lewis go for broke. But it's a pleasure to be reminded, if only once every four years, that subtlety can be overrated.\"<ref name=\"Dangelo\">{{cite news |last=D'Angelo |first=Mike |title=One Fine Ham |work=Esquire.com |date=December 26, 2007 |url=http://www.esquire.com/features/the-screen/danieldaylewis0108 |accessdate=December 31, 2007}}</ref>\n[[Richard Schickel]] in ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' praised ''There Will Be Blood'' as \"one of the most wholly original American movies ever made.\"<ref name=\"Schickel\">{{cite news |last=Schickel |first=Richard |title='There Will Be Blood': An American Tragedy |work=Time.com |date=December 24, 2007 |url=http://www.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,1698168,00.html |accessdate=December 31, 2007}}</ref> Critic Tom Charity, writing about [[CNN]]'s ten-best films list, calls the film the only \"flat-out masterpiece\" of 2007.<ref name=\"Charity\">{{cite news |title=Review: The best (and worst) films of 2007 |work=CNN |date=December 29, 2007 |author=Charity, Tom |accessdate=January 6, 2008 |url=http://www.cnn.com/2007/SHOWBIZ/Movies/12/28/best.2007}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Roger Ebert cropped.jpg|thumb|left|Roger Ebert gave ''There Will Be Blood'' a positive review but in comparing it to ''No Country for Old Men'' he found the McCarthy script for ''No Country'' to be better.]]\nSchickel also named the film one of the Top 10 Movies of 2007, ranking it at #9, calling Daniel Day-Lewis' performance \"astonishing\", and calling the film \"a mesmerizing meditation on the American spirit in all its maddening ambiguities: mean and noble, angry and secretive, hypocritical and more than a little insane in its aspirations.\"<ref>[[Richard Schickel|Schickel, Richard]]: [http://www.time.com/time/specials/2007/top10/article/0,30583,1686204_1686244_1692274,00.html \"The 10 Best Movies\"]; Time.com.</ref> James Christopher, chief film critic for ''[[The Times]]'', published a list in April 2008 of his top 100 films, placing ''There Will Be Blood'' in second place, behind only ''[[Casablanca (film)|Casablanca]]''.<ref>{{cite news |first=James |last=Christopher |title=Top 100 Films |url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/related_features/top_100_films |work=The Times |date=April 27, 2008 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nSome critics were positive toward the work but less laudatory, often criticizing its ending. [[Mick LaSalle]] of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'', challenged the film's high praise by saying \"there should be no need to pretend ''There Will Be Blood'' is a masterpiece just because Anderson sincerely tried to make it one\" and noting that \"the scenes between Day-Lewis and Dano ultimately degenerate into a ridiculous [[burlesque]]\".<ref name=\"SFCreview\">{{cite news |title=Conquering the West, and getting his hands dirty in the process |work=San Francisco Chronicle |date=January 4, 2008 |author=LaSalle, Mick |accessdate=April 19, 2008 |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2008/01/04/DDVCU8QKP.DTL&type=movies}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] assigned the film three and a half out of four stars and wrote, \"''There Will Be Blood'' is the kind of film that is easily called great. I am not sure of its greatness. It was filmed in the same area of Texas used by ''[[No Country for Old Men (film)|No Country for Old Men]]'', and that is a great film, and a perfect one. But ''There Will Be Blood'' is not perfect, and in its imperfections (its unbending characters, its lack of women or any reflection of ordinary society, its ending, its relentlessness) we may see its reach exceeding its grasp.\"<ref>{{cite news | title=''There Will Be Blood'' review \u2013 Roger Ebert | url=http://www.rogerebert.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080103/REVIEWS/801030301/1023 |work=Chicago Sun-Times | date=January 4, 2008}}</ref> Carla Meyer of the ''[[Sacramento Bee]]'', who gave the film the same star rating as Ebert, opined that the final confrontation between Daniel and Eli marked when the work \"stops being a masterpiece and becomes a really good movie. What was grand becomes petty, then overwrought.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Movie review: Brutally real&nbsp;\u2013 Daniel Day Lewis exudes authenticity in oil-field drama 'There Will Be Blood' |work=The Sacramento Bee |date=January 11, 2008 |author=Meyer, Carla |accessdate=May 9, 2008 |url=http://www.sacbee.com/meyer/story/623040.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080330141358/http://www.sacbee.com/meyer/story/623040.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate=March 30, 2008}}</ref> In 2014, Peter Walker of ''[[The Guardian]]'' likewise argued that the scene \"might not be the very worst scene in the history of recent Oscar-garlanded cinema ... but it's perhaps the one most inflated with its own delusional self-importance.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2014/nov/12/there-will-be-blood-my-most-overrated-film |title=There Will be Blood: my most overrated film |last=Walker |first=Peter |newspaper=The Guardian |date=November 12, 2014 |accessdate=January 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSeveral months after LaSalle's initial review of the film, he reiterated that while he still did not consider ''There Will Be Blood'' to be a masterpiece, he wondered if its \"style, an approach, an attitude... might become important in the future.\"<ref name=\"Maximum Strength Mick\">{{cite news |title=Winning the Future: Through What Works Will Our Era Be Remembered? |work=San Francisco Chronicle |date=May 12, 2008 |author=LaSalle, Mick |accessdate=February 15, 2009 |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/blogs/mlasalle/detail?blogid=38&entry_id=26441}}</ref> Since 2008, the film has been included in the book ''[[1001 Movies You Must See Before You Die]]'' and every revised edition released afterwards.<ref>{{cite book |last=Schneider |first=Stephen Jay |title=1001 Movies You Must See Before You Die |publisher=Octopus Publishing Group, London |date=April 10, 2010 |pages=928 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a1MSRAAACAAJ&dq=1001+movies+you+must+see+before+you+die&source=bl&ots=DNzdYOLCHE&sig=BWn6qrwnq9cKuivHANtVooszd48&hl=en&sa=X&ei=O9JeUNOzFY6T0QWlqIDwDg&ved=0CEAQ6AEwAw |isbn=978-1-84403-690-5 |accessdate=September 23, 2012}}</ref> ''[[Total Film]]'' placed it at number three in their list of the 50 best movies of ''Total Film'''s lifetime,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/50-best-movies-of-total-film-magazine-s-lifetime/|title=Total Film - GamesRadar+|publisher=|accessdate=11 January 2017}}</ref> while ''[[The Guardian]]'' ranked it the 17th best arthouse film of all time and the best film of the 21st century.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/oct/20/there-will-blood-anderson-arthouse|title=There Will Be Blood: No 17 best arthouse film of all time|author=Steve Rose|work=the Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The 100 best films of the 21st century |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/sep/13/100-best-films-movies-of-the-21st-century |website=The Guardian |accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Top ten lists ===\nThe film was on the [[American Film Institute]]'s 10 Movies of the Year; AFI's jury said:\n\n<blockquote>\n''There Will Be Blood'' is bravura film-making by one of American film's modern masters. Paul Thomas Anderson's epic poem of savagery, optimism and obsession is a true meditation on America.  The film drills down into the dark heart of capitalism, where domination, not gain, is the ultimate goal. In a career defined by transcendent performances, Daniel Day-Lewis creates a character so rich and so towering, that \"Daniel Plainview\" will haunt the history of film for generations to come.<ref>[http://www.afi.com/tvevents/afiawards07/movies07.aspx \"AFI Movies of the Year Official Selections\"]. ''American Film Institute''. Retrieved November 18, 2012.</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nThe film appeared on many critics' top ten lists of the best films of 2007.<ref name=\"Metacritic07-Top10\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/awards/2007/toptens.shtml |title=Metacritic: 2007 Film Critic Top Ten Lists |accessdate=January 5, 2008 |work=Metacritic |publisher=CBS Interactive |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080102102034/http://www.metacritic.com/film/awards/2007/toptens.shtml <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate=January 2, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"MovieCityNews\">{{cite web |url=http://www.moviecitynews.com/awards/2008/top_ten/00index.html |title=Movie City News: 2007 Film Critic Top Ten Lists |accessdate=January 8, 2008 |work=Movie City News |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080103085851/http://www.moviecitynews.com/awards/2008/top_ten/00index.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate=January 3, 2008}}</ref>\n\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 Ethar Alter, ''[[Giant (magazine)|Giant]]''<ref name=\"MovieCityNews\" />\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 Marjorie Baumgarten, ''[[The Austin Chronicle]]''<ref name=\"Metacritic07-Top10\" />\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 Tom Charity, ''[[CNN]]''<ref name=\"Charity\" />\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 [[Manohla Dargis]], ''[[The New York Times]]''<ref name=\"MovieCityNews\" />\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 David Fear, ''[[Time Out New York]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://movies.msn.com/movies/2007review/top10movieslists |title=2007 Year in Review |accessdate=January 9, 2008 |work=MSN |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080109053939/http://movies.msn.com/movies/2007review/top10movieslists |archive-date=January 9, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 Scott Foundas, ''[[LA Weekly]]''<ref name=\"Metacritic07-Top10\" />\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 Stephen Holden, ''[[The New York Times]]''<ref name=\"Metacritic07-Top10\" />\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 Tod Hill, ''[[Staten Island Advance]]''<ref name=\"MovieCityNews\" />\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 Glenn Kenny, ''[[Premiere (magazine)|Premiere]]''<ref name=\"Metacritic07-Top10\" />\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 Craig Outhier, ''[[Orange County Register]]''<ref name=\"MovieCityNews\" />\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 Keith Phipps, ''[[The A.V. Club]]''<ref name=\"Metacritic07-Top10\" />\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 Ray Pride, ''[[Salon.com]]''<ref name=\"MovieCityNews\" />\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 Mike Russell, ''[[The Oregonian]]''<ref name=\"Metacritic07-Top10\" />\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 Hank Sartin, ''[[Chicago Reader]]''<ref name=\"MovieCityNews\" />\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 Marc Savlov, ''[[The Austin Chronicle]]''<ref name=\"Metacritic07-Top10\" />\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 Mark Slutsky, ''[[Montreal Mirror]]''<ref name=\"MovieCityNews\" />\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 Nick Schager, ''[[Slant Magazine]]''<ref name=\"MovieCityNews\" />\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 Lisa Schwarzbaum, ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''<ref name=\"Metacritic07-Top10\" />\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 Jan Stuart, ''[[Newsday]]''<ref name=\"MovieCityNews\" />\n{{Col-2}}\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 Ella Taylor, ''[[LA Weekly]]''<ref name=\"Metacritic07-Top10\" />\n* 2nd&nbsp;\u2013 David Ansen, ''[[Newsweek]]''<ref name=\"Metacritic07-Top10\" />\n* 2nd&nbsp;\u2013 Nathan Rabin, ''[[The A.V. Club]]''<ref name=\"Metacritic07-Top10\" />\n* 2nd&nbsp;\u2013 Rene Rodriguez, ''[[The Miami Herald]]''<ref name=\"Metacritic07-Top10\" />\n* 2nd&nbsp;\u2013 Scott Tobias, ''[[The A.V. Club]]''<ref name=\"Metacritic07-Top10\" />\n* 3rd&nbsp;\u2013 [[A.O. Scott]], ''[[The New York Times]]'' (tied with ''[[Sweeney Todd: The Demon Barber of Fleet Street (2007 film)|Sweeney Todd: The Demon Barber of Fleet Street]]'')<ref name=\"Metacritic07-Top10\" />\n* 3rd&nbsp;\u2013 Ann Hornaday, ''[[The Washington Post]]''<ref name=\"Metacritic07-Top10\" />\n* 3rd&nbsp;\u2013 Joe Morgenstern, ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''<ref name=\"Metacritic07-Top10\" />\n* 4th&nbsp;\u2013 Desson Thomson, ''[[The Washington Post]]''<ref name=\"Metacritic07-Top10\" />\n* 4th&nbsp;\u2013 [[Ty Burr]], ''[[The Boston Globe]]''<ref name=\"Metacritic07-Top10\" />\n* 5th&nbsp;\u2013 J. Hoberman, ''[[The Village Voice]]''<ref name=\"Metacritic07-Top10\" />\n* 5th&nbsp;\u2013 Shawn Levy, ''[[The Oregonian]]''<ref name=\"Metacritic07-Top10\" />\n* 6th&nbsp;\u2013 Christy Lemire, [[Associated Press]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.columbiatribune.com/2007/Dec/20071227Go!013.asp |title='No Country for Old Men' earns nod from AP critics |accessdate=December 31, 2007 |author=David Germain |author2=Christy Lemire |date=December 27, 2007 |publisher=Associated Press, via Columbia Daily Tribune |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20080103000750/http://www.columbiatribune.com/2007/Dec/20071227Go!013.asp <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate=January 3, 2008}}</ref>\n* 7th&nbsp;\u2013 [[Peter Travers]], ''[[Rolling Stone]]''<ref name=\"Metacritic07-Top10\" />\n* 9th&nbsp;\u2013 Claudia Puig, ''[[USA Today]]''<ref name=\"Metacritic07-Top10\" />\n* 9th&nbsp;\u2013 [[Richard Schickel]], [[Time (magazine)|''TIME'' magazine]]<ref name=\"Metacritic07-Top10\" />\n* 10th&nbsp;\u2013 Lou Lumenick, ''[[New York Post]]''<ref name=\"Metacritic07-Top10\" />\n* Top 10 (listed alphabetically, not ranked)&nbsp;\u2013 [[Dana Stevens (critic)|Dana Stevens]], ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]''<ref name=\"Metacritic07-Top10\" />\n{{Col-end}}\n\n==== Decade-end lists ====\nReview aggregator site [[Metacritic]], when comparing over 40 'top ten of the decade' lists from various notable publications, found ''There Will Be Blood'' to be the most mentioned, appearing on 46% of critics' lists and being ranked the decade's best film on five of them.\n\nIn December 2009, Peter Travers of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' chose the film as the #1 film of the decade, saying:\n<blockquote>Two years after first seeing ''There Will Be Blood'', I am convinced that Paul Thomas Anderson's profound portrait of an American primitive\u2014take that, ''Citizen Kane''\u2014deserves pride of place among the decade's finest. Daniel Day-Lewis gave the best and ballsiest performance of the past 10 years. As Daniel Plainview, a prospector who loots the land of its natural resources in silver and oil to fill his pockets and gargantuan ego, he showed us a man draining his humanity for power. And Anderson, having extended Plainview's rage from Earth to heaven in the form of a corrupt preacher (Paul Dano), managed to \"drink the milkshake\" of other risk-taking directors. If I had to stake the future of film in the next decade on one filmmaker, I'd go with PTA. Even more than ''Boogie Nights'' and ''Magnolia''\u2014his rebel cries from the 1990s\u2014''Blood'' let Anderson put technology at the service of character. The score by Radiohead's Jonny Greenwood was a sonic explosion that reinvented what film music could be. And the images captured by Robert Elswit, a genius of camera and lighting, made visual poetry out of an oil well consumed by flame. For the final word on ''Blood'', I'll quote Plainview: \"It was one goddamn hell of a show.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/photos/gallery/31234572/peter_travers_10_best_movies_of_t/photo/10ml |title=Peter Travers' 10 Best Movies of the Decade |work=Rolling Stone Magazine |date=December 10, 2009 |accessdate=December 10, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100114150503/http://www.rollingstone.com/photos/gallery/31234572/peter_travers_10_best_movies_of_t/photo/10ml |archivedate=January 14, 2010 }}</ref></blockquote>\n\n''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' and ''[[At the Movies (1986 TV program)|At the Movies]]'' critic [[Michael Phillips (critic)|Michael Phillips]] named ''There Will Be Blood'' the decade's best film. Phillips stated:\n<blockquote>This most eccentric and haunting of modern epics is driven by oilman Daniel Plainview, who, in the hands of actor Daniel Day-Lewis, becomes a Horatio Alger story gone horribly wrong. Writer/director Paul Thomas Anderson's camera is as crucial to the films hypnotic pull as the performance at its center. For its evocation of the early 1900s, its relentless focus on one man's fascinating obsessions, and for its inspiring example of how to freely adapt a novel\u2014plus, what I think is the performance of the new century\u2014''There Will Be Blood'' stands alone. The more I see it, the sadder, and stranger, and more visually astounding it grows\u2014and the more it seems to say about the best and worst in the American ethos of rugged individualism. Awfully good!<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bventertainment.go.com/tv/buenavista/atm/specials/bestofthedecade/index.html |title=Best of the Decade |date=December 28, 2009 |accessdate=December 28, 2009}}{{dead link|date=November 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' critic Lisa Schwarzbaum named ''There Will Be Blood'' the decade's best film as well. In her original review, Schwarzbaum stated:\n<blockquote>Anyhow, a fierce story meshing big exterior-oriented themes of American character with an interior-oriented portrait of an impenetrable man (two men, really, including the false prophet Sunday) is only half Anderson's quest, and his exciting achievement. The other half lies in the innovation applied to the telling itself. For a huge picture, There Will Be Blood is exquisitely intimate, almost a collection of sketches. For a long, slow movie, it speeds. For a story set in the fabled bad-old-days past, it's got the terrors of modernity in its DNA. Leaps of romantic chordal grandeur from Brahms' Violin Concerto in D Major announce the launch of a fortune-changing oil well down the road from Eli Sunday's church\u2014and then, much later, announce a kind of end of the world. For bleakness, the movie can't be beat\u2014nor for brilliance.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20168259,00.html |title=There Will Be Blood Review |date=January 9, 2008 |accessdate=January 9, 2008}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn December 2009, the website [[Gawker.com]] determined that ''There Will Be Blood'' is film critics' consensus best film of the decade when aggregating all Best of the Decade lists, stating: \"And when the votes were all in, by a nose, ''There Will Be Blood'' stood alone at the top of the decade, its straw in the whole damn cinema's milkshake.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gawker.com/5428998/there-will-be-blood-wins-the-decade |title=There Will Be Blood Wins the Decade |work=Gawker |date=December 18, 2009 |accessdate=February 7, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100203203506/http://gawker.com/5428998/there-will-be-blood-wins-the-decade |archivedate=February 3, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nThe list of critics who lauded ''There Will Be Blood'' in their assessments of films from the past decade include:\n\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n* ''[[The A.V. Club]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/the-best-films-of-the-00s,35931/4 |title=The best films of the '00s |date=December 3, 2009 |publisher=The A. V Club |accessdate=December 19, 2009}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/6501160/Top-100-movies-defining-the-noughties-00s-in-film.html |title=The films that defined the noughties |date=November 6, 2009 |work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=December 19, 2009 |location=London |first1=David |last1=Gritten |first2=Tim |last2=Robey |first3=Sukhdev |last3=Sandhu}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Guardian]]''<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2010/jan/01/best-films-noughties-there-will-be-blood |title=Best films of the noughties No. 1: There Will Be Blood |date=January 1, 2010 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=January 1, 2010 |location=London |first=Peter |last=Bradshaw}}</ref>\n* ''[[Slant Magazine]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/film/feature/best-of-the-aughts-film/216/page_7 |title=Best of the Aughts: Film |date=February 10, 2010 |work=Slant Magazine |accessdate=February 11, 2010}}</ref>\n* ''[[Time Out New York]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newyork.timeout.com/articles/film/80947/the-tony-top-50-movies-of-the-decade/6.html |title=The TONY Top 50 movies of the decade |date=December 2, 2009 |work=Time Out New York |accessdate=December 31, 2009}}</ref>\n* [[David Denby (film critic)|David Denby]], ''[[The New Yorker]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/tny/2009/12/best-films-of-the-decade-david-denby.html |title=The Best Films of the Decade |date=December 15, 2009 |work=The New Yorker |accessdate=December 19, 2009}}</ref>\n* Scott Foundas, ''[[SF Weekly]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sfweekly.com/2009-12-23/film/best-films-of-the-decade |title=Best Films of the Decade |date=December 21, 2009 |work=SF Weekly |accessdate=December 31, 2009}}</ref>\n* David Germain and [[Christy Lemire]], The [[Associated Press]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.journalgazette.net/article/20091226/ENT01/312269993/1162 |title='Pan's Labyrinth,' 'Once' make cut |date=December 26, 2009 |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=December 31, 2009}}</ref>\n{{Col-2}}\n* Bill Goodykoontz, ''[[The Arizona Republic]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.azcentral.com/thingstodo/movies/articles/2009/12/29/20091229dontmiss0101.html |title=Don't miss: 'There Will Be Blood' |date=December 29, 2009 |work=The Arizona Republic |accessdate=December 31, 2009}}</ref>\n* Ann Hornaday, ''[[The Washington Post]]''<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/story/2009/12/24/ST2009122401455.html |title=Best of the decade: Film |accessdate=December 27, 2009 |work=The Washington Post |first=Ann |last=Hornaday |date=December 27, 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Wesley Morris]], ''[[The Boston Globe]]''<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/ae/movies/articles/2009/12/29/wesley_morriss_top_films_of_the_decade |title=Wesley Morris's best of the decade |date=December 29, 2009 |work=The Boston Globe |accessdate=December 31, 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Michael Phillips (critic)|Michael Phillips]], ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bventertainment.go.com/tv/buenavista/atm/specials/bestofthedecade/index.html |title=Best of the Decade |date=December 28, 2009 |work=At the Movies |accessdate=December 31, 2009}}{{dead link|date=November 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n* Lisa Schwarzbaum, ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://movie-critics.ew.com/2009/12/30/lisas-10-best-movies-of-the-decade |title=Lisa Schwarzbaum's 10 best movies of the decade |date=December 30, 2009 |work=Entertainment Weekly |accessdate=December 31, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100118182535/http://movie-critics.ew.com/2009/12/30/lisas-10-best-movies-of-the-decade/ |archivedate=January 18, 2010 }}</ref>\n* Dana Stevens, ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate Magazine]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slate.com/id/2239354/pagenum/all/#p2 |title=Best Movies: My favorites of the year and the decade |date=December 21, 2009 |work=Slate |accessdate=December 31, 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Peter Travers]], ''[[Rolling Stone]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/photos/gallery/31234572/peter_travers_10_best_movies_of_t/photo/10 |title=Peter Travers' 10 Best Movies of the Decade |date=December 23, 2009 |work=Rolling Stone |accessdate=December 31, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091214153151/http://www.rollingstone.com/photos/gallery/31234572/peter_travers_10_best_movies_of_t/photo/10 |archivedate=December 14, 2009 }}</ref>\n* Chris Vognar, ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/ent/stories/DN-filmdecade_0101gd.State.Edition1.168e8ad.html |title=Chris Vognar's top 25 films of the decade |date=December 31, 2009 |work=The Dallas Morning News |accessdate=December 31, 2009}}</ref>\n{{Col-end}}\n\nIn 2016, it was voted the #3 [[100 Greatest Films of the 21st Century|best film of the 21st century]] as picked by 177 film critics from around the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20160819-the-21st-centurys-100-greatest-films|title=The 21st Century\u2019s 100 greatest films|first=23 August|last=2016|publisher=|accessdate=11 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe February 2020 issue of ''[[New York Magazine]]'' lists ''There Will Be Blood'' alongside ''[[Citizen Kane]]'', ''[[Sunset Boulevard (film)|Sunset Boulevard]]'', ''[[Dr, Strangelove]]'', ''[[Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid]]'', ''[[The Conversation]]'', ''[[Nashville (film)|Nashville]]'', ''[[Taxi Driver]]'', ''[[The Elephant Man (film)|The Elephant Man]]'', ''[[Pulp Fiction]]'', ''[[In the Bedroom]]'', and ''[[Roma (2018 film)|Roma]]'' as \"''The Best Movies That Lost Best Picture at the Oscars'.\" <ref name=\"The Best Movies That Lost Best Picture at the Oscars\">{{cite news|title=The Best Movies That Lost Best Picture at the Oscars|url=https://www.vulture.com/article/best-oscar-best-picture-losers.html|magazine=[[New York Magazine]]|accessdate=2020-02-24}}</ref>\n\n=== Box office performance ===\nThe first public screening of ''There Will Be Blood'' was on September 29, 2007, at [[Fantastic Fest]] in [[Austin, Texas|Austin]], [[Texas]]. The film was released on December 26, 2007, in [[New York City]] and [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]] where it grossed [[United States dollar|US$]]190,739 on its opening weekend. The film then opened in 885 theaters in selected markets on January 25, 2008, grossing $4.8 million on its opening weekend. The film went on to make $40.2 million in North America and $35.9 million in the rest of the world, with a worldwide total of $76.1 million, well above its $25 million budget.<ref name=\"BoxOfficeMojo\" /> But the prints and advertising cost for the film's [[United States]] release was about $40 million.<ref>[http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20181242,00.html \"EW.com\"]. Retrieved November 18, 2012.</ref>\n\n=== Home media ===\nThe film was released on [[DVD]] on April 8, 2008. It was released with one and two-disc editions, both are packaged in a cardboard case. Anderson has refused to record an [[audio commentary]] for the film.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.awardsdaily.com/?p=65#more-65 |title=There Will Be No Commentary |accessdate=2008-03-11 |work=Awards Daily}}</ref> A [[HD DVD]] release was announced, but later canceled due to the discontinuation of the format. A [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]] edition was released on June 3, 2008. The film has grossed $23,604,823 through DVD sales.<ref name=\"The-Numbers\">{{cite web |title=There Will Be Blood |url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/2007/TWBLD.php |work=The-Numbers.com |accessdate=November 6, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe line, \"I drink your milkshake!\", used by Daniel Plainview to explain his technique has been used in other media repeatedly. For example:\n* In season 24 of ''[[Jeopardy!]]'', \"I Drink Your Milkshake\" was the title of a category about milkshakes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.j-archive.com/showgame.php?game_id=2541&highlight=+i+drink+your+milkshake+ |title=Jeopardy! Show #5498 |website=J! Archive |accessdate=2009-01-02}}</ref>\n* [[Jon Stewart]], host of ''[[The Daily Show]]'' and the [[80th Academy Awards]] (for which ''There Will Be Blood'' was nominated for eight Oscars), has referenced the phrase \"I drink your milkshake\" several times on his show in response to news involving oil drilling, including during interviews with [[Ted Koppel]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thedailyshow.com/video/index.jhtml?videoId=174804&title=Ted-Koppel |title=Ted Koppel |date=June 26, 2008 |website=The Daily Show |accessdate=2009-01-02}}</ref> and [[Nancy Pelosi]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thedailyshow.com/video/index.jhtml?videoId=177587&title=Nancy-Pelosi |title=Nancy Pelosi |date=July 28, 2008 |website=The Daily Show |accessdate=January 2, 2009}}</ref>\n* In February 2008, a ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' skit featured a [[Food Network]] show called ''I Drink Your Milkshake'', in which Daniel Plainview ([[Bill Hader]]) and H. W. ([[Amy Poehler]]) travel from state to state looking for the perfect milkshake.<ref>{{cite news|title=Milkshakes |work=NBC |publisher=Hulu.com |url=http://www.hulu.com/watch/10232/saturday-night-live-milkshakes |accessdate=2008-11-08 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5cB1Pmcig?url=http://www.hulu.com/watch/10232/saturday-night-live-milkshakes |archivedate=2008-11-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* The ''[[South Park]]'' episode \"[[Breast Cancer Show Ever]]\" (October 15, 2008) parodies the final scene of the film: after [[List of students at South Park Elementary#Wendy Testaburger|Wendy]] beats up [[Eric Cartman|Cartman]], [[List of staff at South Park Elementary#Mr. Mackey|Mr. Mackey]] approaches and says, \"Wendy!\", to which she replies, \"I'm finished,\" as Cartman lies face down in blood.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.southparkstudios.com/clips/188250 |title=Wendy vs. Cartman |website=South Park Studios |accessdate=2009-01-02}}</ref>\n* In ''[[Bojack Horseman]]'', [[Princess Carolyn]] taunts Bojack during a 2007 flashback episode with the line \"I drink your milkshake!\", assuring him it will be funny in about a year.\n* In ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]'', flashbacks set in 2008 have Troy talking about several movies from the time, and includes him quoting \"I drink your milkshake!\" and claiming that \"that will never get old.\"\n\n== Accolades ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date of ceremony\n! Award\n! Category\n! Recipient(s)\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"9\" | February 24, 2008\n| rowspan=\"9\" | [[80th Academy Awards|Academy Awards]]<ref name=\"80thAA\">{{cite web |url=http://www.oscars.org/80academyawards/nominees/index.html |title=Nominees \u2013 80th Annual Academy Awards |accessdate=2008-01-22 |work=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080123152423/http://www.oscars.org/80academyawards/nominees/index.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate=2008-01-23}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Academy Award fo